1
00:02:53,904 --> 00:02:56,506
You see? You see
the symbolism of it?

2
00:02:56,506 --> 00:02:58,508
Capital and Labor
destroy each other.

3
00:02:58,509 --> 00:03:01,345
It teaches a moral lesson.
It has social significance.

4
00:03:01,346 --> 00:03:03,482
Who wants to see that kind of stuff?
It gives me the creeps.

5
00:03:03,482 --> 00:03:05,484
Tell him how long it played
in the Music Hall.

6
00:03:05,485 --> 00:03:07,487
It was held over a fifth week.

7
00:03:07,488 --> 00:03:09,623
Who goes to the Music Hall?
Communists!

8
00:03:09,623 --> 00:03:12,459
Communists? This picture's
an answer to Communists!

9
00:03:12,460 --> 00:03:14,429
It shows we're awake...

10
00:03:14,430 --> 00:03:16,432
and not dunking our heads in the sand
like a bunch of ostriches!

11
00:03:16,432 --> 00:03:18,768
I want this picture to be
a commentary on modern conditions.

12
00:03:18,769 --> 00:03:21,271
Stark realism. The problems
that confront the average man.

13
00:03:21,272 --> 00:03:23,274
- But with a little sex.
- A little,
but I don't want to stress it.

14
00:03:23,275 --> 00:03:25,277
I want this picture
to be a document.

15
00:03:25,277 --> 00:03:27,279
I want to hold
a mirror up to life.

16
00:03:27,280 --> 00:03:29,282
I want this to be
a picture of dignity--

17
00:03:29,282 --> 00:03:31,751
- a true canvas
of the suffering of humanity.
- But with a little sex.

18
00:03:31,752 --> 00:03:33,754
- With a little sex in it.
- How about a nice musical?

19
00:03:33,755 --> 00:03:35,757
How can you talk about musicals
at a time like this,

20
00:03:35,757 --> 00:03:37,759
with the world
committing suicide?

21
00:03:37,760 --> 00:03:39,762
With corpses piling up
in the street,

22
00:03:39,763 --> 00:03:41,799
with grim death gargling at you
from every corner,

23
00:03:41,799 --> 00:03:44,034
- with people slaughtered like sheep!
- Maybe they'd like to forget.

24
00:03:44,035 --> 00:03:47,340
Then why did they hold this one over
for a fifth week? For the ushers?

25
00:03:47,340 --> 00:03:49,442
- It died in Pittsburgh.
- Like a dog.

26
00:03:49,443 --> 00:03:51,445
- What do they know in Pittsburgh?
- They know what they like.

27
00:03:51,445 --> 00:03:53,447
If they knew what they liked,
they wouldn't live in Pittsburgh.

28
00:03:53,448 --> 00:03:56,584
If you pandered to the public,
you'd still be in the horse age.

29
00:03:56,585 --> 00:03:58,787
- You think we're not?
Look at Hopalong Cassidy.
- You look at him!

30
00:03:58,787 --> 00:04:02,058
We'd still be making Keystone chases,
bathing beauties, custard pie--

31
00:04:02,058 --> 00:04:04,060
- And a fortune.
- A fortune.

32
00:04:04,061 --> 00:04:06,397
Of course I'm just a minor
employee here, Mr. LeBrand--

33
00:04:06,398 --> 00:04:08,400
He's starting that one again.

34
00:04:08,400 --> 00:04:11,503
I wanted to make you
something outstanding--
something you could be proud of,

35
00:04:11,504 --> 00:04:13,940
something that would realize
the potentialities of film...

36
00:04:13,941 --> 00:04:16,744
as the sociological
and artistic medium that it is.

37
00:04:16,745 --> 00:04:18,747
With a little sex in it.
Something like--

38
00:04:18,748 --> 00:04:21,617
- Something like Capra. I know.
- What's the matter with Capra?

39
00:04:21,617 --> 00:04:23,619
- Look, you want to make
O Brother, Where Art Thou?
- Yes.

40
00:04:23,620 --> 00:04:25,622
- Now, wait a minute!
- Then go ahead and make it!

41
00:04:25,623 --> 00:04:27,625
For what you're getting,
I can't afford to argue with you.

42
00:04:27,625 --> 00:04:29,627
That's a fine way to start a man out
on a million-dollar production.

43
00:04:29,628 --> 00:04:31,630
You want it, you've got it!

44
00:04:31,631 --> 00:04:33,633
I can take it on the chin.
I've taken it before.

45
00:04:33,633 --> 00:04:36,036
- Not from me you haven't.
- Not from you, Sully, that's true.

46
00:04:36,037 --> 00:04:38,039
Not with pictures like
So Long Sarong,

47
00:04:38,040 --> 00:04:40,042
Hey, Hey, In the Hayloft,
Ants in Your Plants of 1939--

48
00:04:40,042 --> 00:04:43,045
But they weren't about tramps,
lockouts, sweatshops,

49
00:04:43,046 --> 00:04:46,650
people eating garbage in alleys
and living in piano boxes and ashcans.

50
00:04:46,650 --> 00:04:48,652
- And phooey!
- They're about nice,
clean young people...

51
00:04:48,653 --> 00:04:50,655
who fell in love--
with laughter and music and legs.

52
00:04:50,655 --> 00:04:52,657
Now take that scene in
Hey, Hey, In the Hayloft--

53
00:04:52,658 --> 00:04:54,660
But you don't realize
conditions have changed.

54
00:04:54,661 --> 00:04:56,663
There isn't any work.
There isn't any food.

55
00:04:56,663 --> 00:04:58,665
- These are troublous times.
- What do you know about trouble?

56
00:04:58,666 --> 00:05:00,668
- What do I know about trouble?
- Yes, what do you know about trouble?

57
00:05:00,668 --> 00:05:02,670
- What do you mean, what
do I know about trouble?
-Just what I'm saying.

58
00:05:02,671 --> 00:05:04,673
You want to make a picture
about garbage cans--

59
00:05:04,674 --> 00:05:06,676
When did you eat
your last meal out of one?

60
00:05:06,676 --> 00:05:08,678
- What's that got to do with it?
- He's asking you.

61
00:05:08,679 --> 00:05:10,681
You want an epic about misery--

62
00:05:10,682 --> 00:05:12,684
you want to show hungry people
sleeping in doorways.

63
00:05:12,684 --> 00:05:14,486
With newspapers around them.

64
00:05:14,487 --> 00:05:16,489
You want to grind
10,000 feet of hard luck,

65
00:05:16,489 --> 00:05:18,491
- and all I'm asking you is,
what do you know about hard luck?
- Yes!

66
00:05:18,492 --> 00:05:20,894
- What do you mean?
Don't you think I've--
- No.

67
00:05:20,895 --> 00:05:22,897
- What?
- You have not.

68
00:05:22,897 --> 00:05:24,899
I sold newspapers
till I was 20,

69
00:05:24,900 --> 00:05:26,902
then I worked in a shoe store and
put myself through law school at night.

70
00:05:26,903 --> 00:05:28,905
- Where were you at 20?
- I was in college.

71
00:05:28,905 --> 00:05:31,375
When I was 13 I supported three sisters,
two brothers and a widowed mother.

72
00:05:31,376 --> 00:05:33,378
- Where were you at 13?
- I was in boarding school.

73
00:05:33,379 --> 00:05:35,781
- I'm sorry.
- You don't have to be
ashamed of it, Sully.

74
00:05:35,781 --> 00:05:37,916
That's the reason your pictures
have been so light, so cheerful,
so inspiring.

75
00:05:37,917 --> 00:05:39,919
They don't stink with messages.

76
00:05:39,920 --> 00:05:41,922
That's why I paid you
500 a week when you were 24.

77
00:05:41,922 --> 00:05:43,924
- 750 at 25.
- 1,000 when you were 26.

78
00:05:43,925 --> 00:05:46,661
- When I was 26, I was getting 18.
- 2,000 at 27.

79
00:05:46,662 --> 00:05:48,931
- I was getting 25 then.
- 3,000 after Thanks for Yesterday.

80
00:05:48,931 --> 00:05:50,933
4,000 after Ants in Your Plants.

81
00:05:50,934 --> 00:05:52,936
I suppose you're trying to tell me
I don't know what trouble is.

82
00:05:52,937 --> 00:05:54,939
- Yes!
- In a nice way, Sully.

83
00:05:54,939 --> 00:05:57,575
You're absolutely right.
I haven't any idea what it is.

84
00:05:57,576 --> 00:05:59,812
People always like what they don't
know anything about.

85
00:05:59,813 --> 00:06:03,551
I had a lot of nerve wanting to make
a picture about human suffering.

86
00:06:03,551 --> 00:06:07,545
You're a gentleman to admit it, Sully,
but then, you are anyway.

87
00:06:07,689 --> 00:06:10,692
How about making
Ants in Your Plants of 1941?

88
00:06:10,693 --> 00:06:12,829
- You can have Bob Hope, Mary Martin--
- Maybe Bing Crosby.

89
00:06:12,830 --> 00:06:14,765
- The Abbott Dancers.
- MaybeJack Benny and Rochester.

90
00:06:14,765 --> 00:06:16,767
- A big-name band.
- What?

91
00:06:16,768 --> 00:06:19,204
Oh, no. I want to make
O Brother, Where Art Thou?

92
00:06:19,205 --> 00:06:21,207
But I'll tell you
what I'm gonna do first.

93
00:06:21,207 --> 00:06:23,209
I'm going down to wardrobe
to get some old clothes,

94
00:06:23,210 --> 00:06:25,212
- some old shoes,
- Huh?

95
00:06:25,213 --> 00:06:27,515
- and I'm gonna start out
with ten cents in my pocket.
- What?

96
00:06:27,515 --> 00:06:29,517
I don't know where I'm going,
but I'm not coming back...

97
00:06:29,518 --> 00:06:31,520
- till I know what trouble is.
- What?

98
00:06:31,520 --> 00:06:33,522
Don't worry, you can
take me off salary.

99
00:06:33,523 --> 00:06:35,792
Who's talking about
taking you off salary?

100
00:06:35,793 --> 00:06:38,229
- So long. Thanks for the idea.
- Wait! Don't be so impulsive.

101
00:06:38,230 --> 00:06:40,232
- How soon will you be back?
- I don't know.

102
00:06:40,232 --> 00:06:42,234
Maybe a week, maybe a month,
maybe a year.

103
00:06:42,235 --> 00:06:44,771
Don't worry about me. And thanks,
Dracula. You gave me a great idea.

104
00:06:44,772 --> 00:06:48,677
I gave you--

105
00:06:48,677 --> 00:06:50,679
- Now look what you've done.
- Yeah-- What I've done?

106
00:06:50,679 --> 00:06:52,681
With your lies
about selling newspapers!

107
00:06:52,682 --> 00:06:54,951
I sold as many newspapers
as you supported a family at 13.

108
00:06:54,952 --> 00:06:57,955
- I opened a shooting gallery.
- With money you borrowed
from your uncle.

109
00:06:57,956 --> 00:07:00,258
- We better insure him for a million.
- He's worth more.

110
00:07:00,258 --> 00:07:03,261
- The bonehead.
- Yes, but what a genius.

111
00:07:03,262 --> 00:07:05,698
Get me a copy of that
O Brother, Where Art Thou?

112
00:07:05,699 --> 00:07:07,701
I guess I'll have
to read it now.

113
00:07:07,702 --> 00:07:11,696
Make that two copies.
Why should I suffer alone?

114
00:07:19,049 --> 00:07:21,819
- How's this?
- Isn't that overdoing it, a bit sir?

115
00:07:21,820 --> 00:07:24,623
Why break their hearts?

116
00:07:24,624 --> 00:07:26,826
All right.
Let's try that one again.

117
00:07:26,826 --> 00:07:29,228
I think this one's
sufficiently seedy, sir.

118
00:07:29,229 --> 00:07:31,665
There's no use overplaying it,
is there, sir?

119
00:07:31,666 --> 00:07:35,660
[ Telephone Ringing ]

120
00:07:39,809 --> 00:07:41,811
Yes?

121
00:07:41,812 --> 00:07:44,248
- Your wife is on one, sir.
- What does she want?

122
00:07:44,249 --> 00:07:47,554
I suspect it has something to do
with today's being the 15th.

123
00:07:47,554 --> 00:07:50,156
- [ Laughs ]
- Payday. All right, put her on.

124
00:07:50,157 --> 00:07:52,960
You may connect Mrs. Sullivan.

125
00:07:52,961 --> 00:07:54,963
Yes?

126
00:07:54,963 --> 00:07:58,267
You don't happen to remember
what day this is, do you, dear?

127
00:07:58,267 --> 00:08:00,703
Yes, I happen to remember
what day it is.

128
00:08:00,704 --> 00:08:04,008
No, I haven't forgotten anything.
Have you?

129
00:08:04,008 --> 00:08:06,844
Perhaps I could be a little
more polite, Mrs. Sullivan,

130
00:08:06,845 --> 00:08:09,248
but somehow, when I talk to you
I don't feel polite.

131
00:08:09,249 --> 00:08:11,284
I regret it,
but that's the way it is.

132
00:08:11,284 --> 00:08:13,720
I don't know whether
I signed it or not.

133
00:08:13,721 --> 00:08:15,723
I always close my eyes
when I sign your check.

134
00:08:15,724 --> 00:08:18,226
Maybe I signed the blotter.

135
00:08:18,226 --> 00:08:20,729
[ Clicking ]

136
00:08:20,730 --> 00:08:23,232
Have you made out
the Panther Woman's check yet?

137
00:08:23,233 --> 00:08:26,136
You better get it down to her before
she comes up here with the sheriff.

138
00:08:26,137 --> 00:08:28,139
She has a very peculiar
sense of humor.

139
00:08:28,139 --> 00:08:30,241
Good morning, sir.

140
00:08:30,242 --> 00:08:32,278
Good morning, Burrows.
How do you like it?

141
00:08:32,279 --> 00:08:35,048
I don't like it at all, sir.
Fancy dress, I take it?

142
00:08:35,048 --> 00:08:37,050
- What's the matter with it?
- I have never been sympathetic...

143
00:08:37,051 --> 00:08:39,854
- to the caricaturing
of the poor and needy, sir.
- Who's caricaturing?

144
00:08:39,855 --> 00:08:41,857
Burrows doesn't know
about the expedition, sir.

145
00:08:41,858 --> 00:08:44,260
I'm going out on the road to find out
what it's like to be poor and needy,

146
00:08:44,260 --> 00:08:46,262
and then I'm going
to make a picture about it.

147
00:08:46,263 --> 00:08:48,399
If you'll permit me to say so, sir,
the subject is not an interesting one.

148
00:08:48,400 --> 00:08:50,402
The poor know all about poverty...

149
00:08:50,402 --> 00:08:52,771
and only the morbid rich
would find the topic glamorous.

150
00:08:52,772 --> 00:08:54,774
But I'm doing it for the poor.
Don't you understand?

151
00:08:54,775 --> 00:08:56,777
I doubt if they would
appreciate it, sir.

152
00:08:56,777 --> 00:09:00,014
They rather resent the invasion of their
privacy, I believe quite properly, sir.

153
00:09:00,015 --> 00:09:03,018
Also, such excursions can be
extremely dangerous, sir.

154
00:09:03,019 --> 00:09:06,155
I worked for a gentleman once
who likewise, with two friends,

155
00:09:06,156 --> 00:09:10,161
accoutred themselves as you have,
sir, and then went out for a lark.

156
00:09:10,161 --> 00:09:12,163
They have not been
heard from since.

157
00:09:12,164 --> 00:09:14,299
- That was some time ago?
- 1912, sir.

158
00:09:14,300 --> 00:09:17,938
- Huh.
- You see, sir, rich people...

159
00:09:17,938 --> 00:09:20,241
and theorists--
who are usually rich people--

160
00:09:20,241 --> 00:09:22,243
think of poverty in the negative,

161
00:09:22,244 --> 00:09:24,246
as the lack of riches--

162
00:09:24,247 --> 00:09:26,416
as disease might be called
the lack of health.

163
00:09:26,416 --> 00:09:29,452
But it isn't, sir.
Poverty is not the lack of anything,

164
00:09:29,453 --> 00:09:32,256
but a positive plague,
virulent in itself,

165
00:09:32,257 --> 00:09:35,427
contagious as cholera,
with filth, criminality,

166
00:09:35,428 --> 00:09:39,266
vice and despair as only
a few of its symptoms.

167
00:09:39,266 --> 00:09:43,137
It is to be stayed away from,
even for purposes of study.

168
00:09:43,137 --> 00:09:45,239
It is to be shunned.

169
00:09:45,240 --> 00:09:47,409
You seem to have made
quite a study of it.

170
00:09:47,410 --> 00:09:51,148
Quite unwillingly, sir.
Will that be all, sir?

171
00:09:51,148 --> 00:09:55,142
- Thanks.
- Very good, sir.

172
00:09:56,756 --> 00:09:59,025
He gets a little bit gruesome
every once in a while.

173
00:09:59,025 --> 00:10:01,894
Yeah.
Always reading books, sir.

174
00:10:01,895 --> 00:10:04,431
- Oh.
- As a matter of fact, sir,

175
00:10:04,432 --> 00:10:07,435
I don't like the idea of a gentleman
of your inexperience...

176
00:10:07,436 --> 00:10:09,905
leaving with only ten cents
in his pockets,

177
00:10:09,906 --> 00:10:12,042
so I took
the extreme liberty, sir,

178
00:10:12,042 --> 00:10:14,778
of having a studio
identification card...

179
00:10:14,779 --> 00:10:17,115
sewed into the sole
of each of your boots.

180
00:10:17,116 --> 00:10:20,487
You'd think I was a child.
The whole purpose of this expedition--

181
00:10:20,487 --> 00:10:24,024
- [ All Talking ]
- All right, all right, all right.

182
00:10:24,024 --> 00:10:26,794
Before you all get started,
I just want to tell you one thing--

183
00:10:26,795 --> 00:10:28,930
- My mind is made up.
- Nobody's here to argue, Sully.

184
00:10:28,930 --> 00:10:30,932
- I know.
- You know that your slightest wish--

185
00:10:30,933 --> 00:10:33,202
We talked it all over,
and there's something to the idea.

186
00:10:33,203 --> 00:10:35,205
- There's a great deal to it.
- Stupendous.

187
00:10:35,205 --> 00:10:37,474
Cassy has it all worked out. It's safe
as a church, big as a cathedral.

188
00:10:37,475 --> 00:10:39,477
Bigger!
It's the story of the year.

189
00:10:39,478 --> 00:10:41,580
It'll make the front page
of every newspaper in the country.

190
00:10:41,580 --> 00:10:43,349
- I'm sending five of my boys--
- With me in charge.

191
00:10:43,350 --> 00:10:45,218
An advance agent in front
and a follow-up behind.

192
00:10:45,219 --> 00:10:47,255
- A cook and a still man.
- I want lots of 8x10's.

193
00:10:47,255 --> 00:10:49,390
-Now, listen--
-I'm revamping that lovely land yacht...

194
00:10:49,391 --> 00:10:51,393
that Demille used
in Northwest Mounted.

195
00:10:51,393 --> 00:10:54,229
- It follows at a discreet dis--
- Hot coffee, sandwiches,
and a bar in back.

196
00:10:54,230 --> 00:10:57,100
It's connected to the studio
by shortwave, and it also carries--

197
00:10:57,101 --> 00:10:59,136
- A hot shower and a secretary.
- And a physician.

198
00:10:59,137 --> 00:11:01,139
Look, I'm trying
to find trouble,

199
00:11:01,139 --> 00:11:03,141
but I won't find it with six acts
of vaudeville on my tail--

200
00:11:03,142 --> 00:11:05,144
at least, not the kind
I'm looking for.

201
00:11:05,145 --> 00:11:07,381
- Be reasonable, Sully.
- I'm reupholstering
it from stem to stern.

202
00:11:07,381 --> 00:11:09,616
- Wait till you see.
- I tell you, I've made up my mind.

203
00:11:09,617 --> 00:11:11,619
- Definitely?
- Definitely.

204
00:11:11,620 --> 00:11:14,190
- In that case,
there's nothing else to do...
- You said it.

205
00:11:14,190 --> 00:11:16,158
but to serve you with this summons
to appear and show cause...

206
00:11:16,159 --> 00:11:18,862
why you should not be restrained
from jeopardizing your unique
and extraordinary services...

207
00:11:18,863 --> 00:11:21,499
- by willfully, recklessly
and unnecessarily--
- Will you please wait a minute!

208
00:11:21,500 --> 00:11:23,936
We have all day, Sully,
but you must realize...

209
00:11:23,936 --> 00:11:27,930
we also have minds,
also made up.

210
00:11:44,530 --> 00:11:47,499
Thus begins this
remarkable expedition...

211
00:11:47,500 --> 00:11:50,972
- into the valley
of the shadow of adversity.
- The shadow of the what?

212
00:11:50,972 --> 00:11:52,974
The valley of the
shadow of adversity.

213
00:11:52,974 --> 00:11:56,378
- It's what you call a paraphrase.
- Alone and unattended--

214
00:11:56,378 --> 00:11:59,682
- With eight stooges.
- I'll write the story,
if it's just the same to you.

215
00:11:59,682 --> 00:12:03,387
Prey to passing prowlers,
poverty and policemen,

216
00:12:03,388 --> 00:12:06,692
- How poetic.
- with only ten cents in his pocket,

217
00:12:06,692 --> 00:12:09,997
-I wish I had what he's got in the bank.
-John Lloyd Sullivan,

218
00:12:09,997 --> 00:12:12,132
the Caliph of Comedy--

219
00:12:12,132 --> 00:12:16,126
- Departed Hollywood
at 4:00 this morning.
- You said it.

220
00:12:20,076 --> 00:12:23,079
- Can I sell you another stack, Doctor?
- Get me some bicarbonate of soda,

221
00:12:23,080 --> 00:12:25,082
and don't call me '' Doctor.''

222
00:12:25,082 --> 00:12:27,518
He was talking to me, I think.
No, thank you.

223
00:12:27,519 --> 00:12:31,224
- You say don't want some
bicarbonate of soda, Doctor?
- Don't call me '' Doctor''!

224
00:12:31,224 --> 00:12:34,628
- No, I don't want
any bicarbonate of soda.
- I thought you said you did.

225
00:12:34,628 --> 00:12:38,099
Well, he don't!

226
00:12:38,099 --> 00:12:40,535
- This place is very depressing.
- So was the breakfast.

227
00:12:40,536 --> 00:12:43,539
Why doesn't he read a book
if he wants to learn something?

228
00:12:43,540 --> 00:12:46,410
-Who, the cook? He could learn plenty.
-No, Sullivan.

229
00:12:46,411 --> 00:12:48,546
- Maybe he don't know how to read.
- The cook?

230
00:12:48,546 --> 00:12:50,548
No, the--

231
00:12:50,549 --> 00:12:54,254
- This is gonna be a great trip.
- Sorry. I must have the wrong number.

232
00:12:54,254 --> 00:12:56,990
That was the lighthouse keeper
on San Clemente Island.

233
00:12:56,991 --> 00:12:58,993
Ask him what
his daughter's doing.

234
00:12:58,994 --> 00:13:02,988
I said the lighthouse keeper
on San Clemente Island.

235
00:13:03,399 --> 00:13:07,393
- How about a little gin rummy?
- I don't drink, thank you.
Never touch it.

236
00:13:12,712 --> 00:13:16,383
[ Tires Squealing ]

237
00:13:16,383 --> 00:13:19,386
- How about a lift, Bud?
- If you don't mind going fast.

238
00:13:19,387 --> 00:13:21,522
I'm studying to be
a whippet tanker.

239
00:13:21,523 --> 00:13:25,517
- Go to it, Lieutenant!
- You're there, General.

240
00:13:50,661 --> 00:13:53,698
- Can a whippet tank make a sharp turn?
- What?

241
00:13:53,698 --> 00:13:55,833
Can a whippet tank
go up a side road?

242
00:13:55,834 --> 00:13:59,272
A whippet tank can go anywhere.
Hang on!

243
00:13:59,272 --> 00:14:03,266
[ Tires Squealing ]

244
00:14:17,430 --> 00:14:21,424
[ Horn Honking ]

245
00:15:19,744 --> 00:15:23,738
[ Screams ]

246
00:15:38,702 --> 00:15:42,174
[ Engine Chugging ]

247
00:15:42,174 --> 00:15:44,576
Thank you, Major.

248
00:15:44,577 --> 00:15:47,713
- This is where I get out.
- She's some tank, ain't she?

249
00:15:47,714 --> 00:15:50,184
In a class by herself.
I never felt anything like it.

250
00:15:50,184 --> 00:15:52,719
Well, I guess I better be
getting to school now, anyway.

251
00:15:52,720 --> 00:15:54,889
Yeah, I guess you better had.
Drive carefully.

252
00:15:54,890 --> 00:15:57,893
- You know me.
- By the way, how old are you?

253
00:15:57,894 --> 00:16:01,888
- Thirteen. So long.
- So long.

254
00:16:04,203 --> 00:16:06,205
What a future.

255
00:16:06,205 --> 00:16:08,207
What were you chasing,
a jackrabbit?

256
00:16:08,208 --> 00:16:11,512
- Felt more like a kangaroo.
- There he is!

257
00:16:11,512 --> 00:16:15,506
- Well, how'd you like it?
- That was a dirty trick, boss.

258
00:16:16,017 --> 00:16:19,589
Look, that was just a rough idea,
unless you play ball with me.

259
00:16:19,589 --> 00:16:21,991
You know I can't do what I started out
to do with you guys chasing me around,

260
00:16:21,992 --> 00:16:23,994
so I'll make you
a fair proposition.

261
00:16:23,995 --> 00:16:25,997
You can go on wherever you like
and take it easy for a couple of weeks,

262
00:16:25,997 --> 00:16:27,999
and I'll join you then
or sooner.

263
00:16:28,000 --> 00:16:30,002
If the boss wants to talk to me,
I'm just up ahead,

264
00:16:30,003 --> 00:16:31,938
mooching a lunch
from a farmer's wife.

265
00:16:31,938 --> 00:16:33,873
Now, is that a square proposition
or isn't it?

266
00:16:33,874 --> 00:16:36,877
- Well, I always wanted to go
to Boulder Dam.
- You're there.

267
00:16:36,878 --> 00:16:38,880
Yeah, well, if you think
I'm going to look at Boulder Dam--

268
00:16:38,880 --> 00:16:40,949
How about
National Yellow Park?

269
00:16:40,950 --> 00:16:43,886
That goes double
for National Yellow Park.

270
00:16:43,887 --> 00:16:46,890
- If you'd said Las Vegas--
- What do they do in Las Vegas?

271
00:16:46,891 --> 00:16:49,761
Everything, Doctor.
It's an education.

272
00:16:49,762 --> 00:16:52,765
All right. I'll meet you in Las Vegas,
on or about the first.

273
00:16:52,766 --> 00:16:56,760
And thanks, kids.
Thanks sincerely.

274
00:17:02,479 --> 00:17:06,473
[ Rooster Crows ]

275
00:17:06,617 --> 00:17:10,611
Yoo-hoo!

276
00:17:11,923 --> 00:17:14,526
- Yes, ma'am?
- Don't get too tired.

277
00:17:14,527 --> 00:17:17,798
Yes, ma'am.

278
00:17:17,798 --> 00:17:21,436
First day's work. You don't suppose
you're overworking him, do you?

279
00:17:21,436 --> 00:17:24,874
Oh, but I doubt it. He seems
very strong. Did you notice his torso?

280
00:17:24,874 --> 00:17:27,610
- I notice that you noticed it.
- Don't be vindictive, dear.

281
00:17:27,611 --> 00:17:31,616
Some people are just naturally
more sensitive to some things
in life than some people.

282
00:17:31,617 --> 00:17:34,453
Some are blind to beauty,
while others--

283
00:17:34,453 --> 00:17:38,447
Even as a little girl,
you were more of acid type,
dear, while I, if you remember--

284
00:17:38,626 --> 00:17:40,795
- I remember better than you do.
- Well, forget it.

285
00:17:40,795 --> 00:17:43,798
And furthermore, I have never done
anything that I was ashamed of, Ursula.

286
00:17:43,799 --> 00:17:46,902
- Neither have I.
- Yes, but nobody ever asked you to.

287
00:17:46,903 --> 00:17:49,472
- Why, Zeffie Kornhauser!
- Now that you've had
your attack for the day,

288
00:17:49,473 --> 00:17:52,476
let's endeavor to recapture our
good humor and remember our breeding.

289
00:17:52,477 --> 00:17:55,480
- Baloney.
- Yes. I do hope he likes it here.

290
00:17:55,481 --> 00:17:58,484
It's so hard to keep a man.
Do you know what I need?

291
00:17:58,485 --> 00:18:00,487
- Yes!
- I need a permanent.

292
00:18:00,487 --> 00:18:02,489
I was thinking of taking in
a picture show,

293
00:18:02,490 --> 00:18:04,492
which brings up the problem
of clothes for the young man.

294
00:18:04,493 --> 00:18:06,495
- It certainly does.
- Do you think...

295
00:18:06,495 --> 00:18:08,364
dearJoseph would mind
if we gave him...

296
00:18:08,365 --> 00:18:10,367
some of the clothes
he has so little need for now?

297
00:18:10,367 --> 00:18:12,369
[ Ursula ]
He's never minded before.

298
00:18:12,370 --> 00:18:15,941
[ Man Mumbling ]

299
00:18:15,941 --> 00:18:19,935
[ Paper Rustling ]

300
00:18:25,887 --> 00:18:29,458
[ Whistle Blows ]

301
00:18:29,458 --> 00:18:31,494
[ Baby Crying ]

302
00:18:31,495 --> 00:18:33,764
[ Baby, Whistle Continue ]

303
00:18:33,765 --> 00:18:37,759
[ Paper Rustling ]

304
00:18:39,906 --> 00:18:43,900
[ Hiccuping ]

305
00:18:52,790 --> 00:18:56,784
[ Crunching ]

306
00:19:13,950 --> 00:19:15,885
- Sleep tight.
- Yes, ma'am.

307
00:19:15,886 --> 00:19:18,022
- And don't let the skeeters bite.
- Yes, ma'am.

308
00:19:18,022 --> 00:19:20,024
- You're sure you have
everything you want?
- Yes, ma'am.

309
00:19:20,025 --> 00:19:22,027
- Absolutely sure?
- Positive.

310
00:19:22,027 --> 00:19:24,896
- But your bed isn't open.
- That's all right.
I'll take care of that.

311
00:19:24,897 --> 00:19:27,500
Oh, nonsense.
That's woman's work.

312
00:19:27,501 --> 00:19:29,770
~ For men must work
and women must weep ~

313
00:19:29,771 --> 00:19:33,765
Or however it goes.
Ahh!

314
00:19:40,651 --> 00:19:43,654
- There. Would you like
a hot water bottle?
- No, ma'am.

315
00:19:43,655 --> 00:19:45,858
- You haven't any pajamas.
- I never use them.

316
00:19:45,859 --> 00:19:47,861
-Joseph wore a nightgown.
- Is that a fact?

317
00:19:47,861 --> 00:19:51,532
Oh, yes.

318
00:19:51,533 --> 00:19:54,804
- Well, I guess there's nothing else.
- No, I guess not.

319
00:19:54,804 --> 00:19:56,939
I'll let you know as soon
as the bathroom is free.

320
00:19:56,939 --> 00:19:58,941
- It's community.
- Ah.

321
00:19:58,942 --> 00:20:00,944
Well, uh--

322
00:20:00,944 --> 00:20:04,682
- Good night.
- Good night.

323
00:20:04,683 --> 00:20:07,954
- Do you think he'll stay?
- I do, do hope so.

324
00:20:07,954 --> 00:20:11,259
[ Lock Clicks ]

325
00:20:11,259 --> 00:20:15,253
[ Chiming ]

326
00:20:39,128 --> 00:20:43,122
Who is it?

327
00:21:42,911 --> 00:21:46,905
[ Fabric Ripping ]

328
00:21:51,255 --> 00:21:55,249
[ Ripping Continues ]

329
00:22:06,776 --> 00:22:10,770
[ Clattering ]

330
00:22:21,162 --> 00:22:24,298
Say, could you give me a lift?
I'm freezing to death.

331
00:22:24,299 --> 00:22:26,868
- What did you fall into?
- Everything there was.

332
00:22:26,868 --> 00:22:29,738
Okay. Hop in the back.
Here. Drape this around you.

333
00:22:29,739 --> 00:22:33,733
- [ Stuttering ]
Thanks a million, buddy.
- Okay.

334
00:22:36,481 --> 00:22:39,184
Come on, Buddy, wake up.
This is as far as I go.

335
00:22:39,185 --> 00:22:42,021
- Huh? What? Who are you?
- Come on, wake up.

336
00:22:42,022 --> 00:22:44,324
I don't want the boss to see you.
We ain't supposed to give lifts.

337
00:22:44,325 --> 00:22:47,195
Sure. Thanks a lot.

338
00:22:47,196 --> 00:22:50,467
- Hey, what city is this?
- That's Hollywood.

339
00:22:50,467 --> 00:22:53,036
- Hollywood?
- You get a chance to see
the moving picture stars.

340
00:22:53,036 --> 00:22:57,030
Well, so long.

341
00:23:05,452 --> 00:23:09,446
~~~[ Big Band On Radio ]

342
00:23:13,930 --> 00:23:17,924
- Good morning.
- Morning.

343
00:23:18,302 --> 00:23:21,305
Give me a cup of coffee and a donut,
if that's enough for it.

344
00:23:21,306 --> 00:23:24,176
- You want it plain
or with powdered sugar?
- With a little cream.

345
00:23:24,177 --> 00:23:28,182
- The sinker?
- Any kind, or some rolls.
I don't care.

346
00:23:28,182 --> 00:23:30,184
Yes, sir.

347
00:23:30,185 --> 00:23:33,054
Give him some ham and eggs.

348
00:23:33,055 --> 00:23:35,057
Yes, ma'am.

349
00:23:35,057 --> 00:23:37,193
That's very kind of you sister,
but I'm not hungry.

350
00:23:37,194 --> 00:23:39,897
A cup of coffee and a sinker
will fix me up fine.

351
00:23:39,898 --> 00:23:42,600
Don't be a sucker.
Give him some ham and eggs.

352
00:23:42,601 --> 00:23:46,595
The way I'm fixed, 35 cents
isn't going to make any difference.

353
00:23:47,073 --> 00:23:50,611
- Here.
- Thanks.

354
00:23:50,611 --> 00:23:52,613
Things a little tough, huh?

355
00:23:52,614 --> 00:23:56,608
I wouldn't be sitting
in an owl wagon for local color.

356
00:23:58,221 --> 00:24:00,490
They locked me out
of my room.

357
00:24:00,491 --> 00:24:03,360
That's too bad.
Well, things are tough everywhere.

358
00:24:03,361 --> 00:24:06,097
War in Europe, strikes over here--
There's no work.

359
00:24:06,098 --> 00:24:10,092
- There's no food.
- Drink your coffee while it's hot.

360
00:24:13,107 --> 00:24:16,445
- What did they lock you
out of your room for?
- Did I ask you any questions?

361
00:24:16,445 --> 00:24:18,447
- I'm sorry.
- It's all right.

362
00:24:18,448 --> 00:24:21,284
- You been in Hollywood long?
- Long enough.

363
00:24:21,285 --> 00:24:24,556
- Trying to crash
the movies or something?
- Something like that.

364
00:24:24,556 --> 00:24:26,558
-I guess that's pretty hard to do, huh?
-I guess so.

365
00:24:26,558 --> 00:24:28,927
I never got close enough
to find out.

366
00:24:28,928 --> 00:24:30,930
- Oh. Sorry.
- Say, who's being sorry for who?

367
00:24:30,931 --> 00:24:33,467
Am I buying you the eggs
or are you buying me the eggs?

368
00:24:33,467 --> 00:24:37,205
- I'd just like to repay you.
- All right, give me a letter
of introduction to Lubitsch.

369
00:24:37,205 --> 00:24:41,199
- I might be able to do that.
Who's Lubitsch?
- Drink your coffee.

370
00:24:42,346 --> 00:24:44,348
- [ Muffled ] Can you act?
- What did you say?

371
00:24:44,349 --> 00:24:46,618
- I said, can you act?
- Sure, I can act.

372
00:24:46,618 --> 00:24:48,953
- Would you like me
to give you a recitation?
- Go ahead.

373
00:24:48,954 --> 00:24:51,624
Skip it. My next act will be
an impersonation...

374
00:24:51,625 --> 00:24:54,094
of a young lady going home--
on the thumb.

375
00:24:54,095 --> 00:24:56,631
- In that outfit?
- What about your own outfit?

376
00:24:56,631 --> 00:24:59,100
- I mean, haven't you got a car?
- No. Have you?

377
00:24:59,101 --> 00:25:01,103
- No, but--
- Then don't get ritzy.

378
00:25:01,104 --> 00:25:03,239
And I'll tell you some
other things I haven't got.

379
00:25:03,239 --> 00:25:05,375
I haven't got a yacht,
or a pearl necklace,

380
00:25:05,376 --> 00:25:07,378
or a fur coat,
or a country seat,

381
00:25:07,379 --> 00:25:09,381
or even a winter seat.

382
00:25:09,381 --> 00:25:11,950
I could use a new girdle, too.

383
00:25:11,951 --> 00:25:14,620
I wish I could give you some
of the things you need.

384
00:25:14,621 --> 00:25:18,626
[ Laughing ] You wouldn't be trying
to lead me astray, would you?

385
00:25:18,626 --> 00:25:20,929
You know, the nice thing about
buying food for a man...

386
00:25:20,930 --> 00:25:23,198
is that you don't have
to laugh at his jokes.

387
00:25:23,199 --> 00:25:26,938
Just think-- if you were some big shot,
like a casting director,

388
00:25:26,938 --> 00:25:29,307
I'd be staring into
your bridgework saying,

389
00:25:29,307 --> 00:25:32,276
''Yes, Mr. Smearkase.
No, Mr. Smearkase.

390
00:25:32,277 --> 00:25:34,546
''Not really, Mr. Smearkase.

391
00:25:34,547 --> 00:25:38,419
Oh, Mr. Smearkase,
that's my knee.''

392
00:25:38,419 --> 00:25:41,355
Give Mr. Smearkase another
cup of coffee. Make it two.

393
00:25:41,356 --> 00:25:43,358
- Want a piece of pie?
- No thanks, kid.

394
00:25:43,359 --> 00:25:46,095
Why, Mr. smearkase, aren't you
getting a little familiar?

395
00:25:46,096 --> 00:25:48,098
Look--

396
00:25:48,098 --> 00:25:50,100
Thanks.

397
00:25:50,101 --> 00:25:52,236
Look, if you wanted to stay
in Hollywood a little longer--

398
00:25:52,237 --> 00:25:54,440
I don't want to stay
in Hollywood a little longer.

399
00:25:54,440 --> 00:25:56,675
I've used up all my money,
all my going-home money.

400
00:25:56,676 --> 00:25:58,979
I was just gonna say,
I have a friend that's out of town...

401
00:25:58,980 --> 00:26:00,982
and you might be able to stay
at his place for a couple of weeks...

402
00:26:00,982 --> 00:26:03,985
and maybe by then things
will break a little better for you.

403
00:26:03,986 --> 00:26:05,988
- He might even be able
to help you a little.
- No, thanks.

404
00:26:05,989 --> 00:26:07,991
There's no strings
to this, kid.

405
00:26:07,991 --> 00:26:10,126
I know you don't know who I am, but
I used to know a few people around here.

406
00:26:10,127 --> 00:26:12,129
And this guy's
really out of town.

407
00:26:12,130 --> 00:26:14,399
And you know a way in
through the window. No, thanks.

408
00:26:14,399 --> 00:26:16,768
- No. I'm pretty sure
that in this case--
- I'm going home, big boy.

409
00:26:16,769 --> 00:26:19,005
I can get a ride out of here
in a little while.

410
00:26:19,006 --> 00:26:23,000
I don't like to think of you
asking a bunch of thugs
for lifts along the highway.

411
00:26:23,044 --> 00:26:27,038
- Then don't think about it.
- You mean you'd just get
in any car that comes along?

412
00:26:27,082 --> 00:26:31,087
- Anything but a Stanley Steamer.
My uncle blew up in one.
- That's terrible.

413
00:26:31,087 --> 00:26:33,723
You can't tell what kind of a heel
is apt to be behind the wheel.

414
00:26:33,724 --> 00:26:35,726
All heels are
pretty much the same.

415
00:26:35,727 --> 00:26:38,096
- Look.
- Yes, Mr. Smearkase?

416
00:26:38,097 --> 00:26:40,533
This friend of mine-- the guy I was
telling you about that's out of town--

417
00:26:40,533 --> 00:26:43,102
I'm sure he wouldn't mind
if I borrowed his car.

418
00:26:43,103 --> 00:26:46,574
- What is it, a street car?
- It's a car. Just wait here.

419
00:26:46,574 --> 00:26:48,576
You're just going to get
yourself in trouble.

420
00:26:48,577 --> 00:26:52,115
I'm not going to get myself in trouble.
I'm going to repay you.

421
00:26:52,115 --> 00:26:54,251
That isn't necessary,
big boy.

422
00:26:54,252 --> 00:26:56,254
Someday, when your ship
comes in,

423
00:26:56,254 --> 00:26:58,823
you can buy somebody that's hungry
some ham and eggs and be all square.

424
00:26:58,824 --> 00:27:02,262
That's fine. Just wait here
and I'll be back before you can say--

425
00:27:02,262 --> 00:27:04,264
- What was that big director's name?
- Lubitsch.

426
00:27:04,265 --> 00:27:06,267
Lubitsch.

427
00:27:06,267 --> 00:27:08,869
Say, this is some car.

428
00:27:08,870 --> 00:27:10,872
Yes. Now, where
would you like to go?

429
00:27:10,873 --> 00:27:14,745
Could you drop me off at, uh--
Or maybe that'd be too far.

430
00:27:14,745 --> 00:27:18,383
- That depends entirely on where it is.
- Would Chicago be too far?

431
00:27:18,383 --> 00:27:21,519
- Chicago?
You mean Chicago, Illinois?
- Yes.

432
00:27:21,520 --> 00:27:24,256
I wasn't actually thinking
of driving as far as Chicago.

433
00:27:24,257 --> 00:27:26,259
That's all right.
You can drop me anywhere.

434
00:27:26,259 --> 00:27:28,261
I just happened to think
of Chicago because...

435
00:27:28,262 --> 00:27:30,798
that's a little better than halfway and
I can easily hitch a ride out of there.

436
00:27:30,799 --> 00:27:34,404
- Where do you live, Bermuda?
- You don't have to get funny.

437
00:27:34,404 --> 00:27:37,140
I didn't ask you for a ride.
You can drop me anywhere.

438
00:27:37,141 --> 00:27:39,410
Wait a minute. How's this?

439
00:27:39,411 --> 00:27:41,413
Suppose you drop me off somewhere
and you go leisurely home...

440
00:27:41,413 --> 00:27:43,415
and I'll pick up the car later.

441
00:27:43,416 --> 00:27:45,418
That's what you call an idea.

442
00:27:45,418 --> 00:27:47,420
You don't happen to operate
out of a booby hatch, do you?

443
00:27:47,421 --> 00:27:50,725
You better drop me at the next
corner and take this bus back
where you stole it from.

444
00:27:50,725 --> 00:27:54,719
Don't talk nonsense. I left a note
saying I was taking the car--

445
00:27:55,131 --> 00:27:57,566
-Or did I?
-It would be nice if you could remember.

446
00:27:57,567 --> 00:28:00,403
Would be funny, though,
if they arrested me for taking it.

447
00:28:00,404 --> 00:28:02,406
A panic.
Who does it belong to?

448
00:28:02,407 --> 00:28:05,444
- Belongs to a picture director--
a guy named Sullivan.
- Oh.

449
00:28:05,445 --> 00:28:07,447
- You never heard of him?
- No.

450
00:28:07,447 --> 00:28:09,582
He's made quite a few pictures.

451
00:28:09,583 --> 00:28:11,619
Ants In Your Plants of 1939.

452
00:28:11,619 --> 00:28:13,854
- Did he do that?
- Yeah. Did you see it?

453
00:28:13,855 --> 00:28:16,658
- Yes.
- Well? Well, did you like it?

454
00:28:16,659 --> 00:28:20,653
-Not much.
-Some people thought it was pretty good.

455
00:28:20,797 --> 00:28:22,799
I don't care for musicals.
They hurt my ears.

456
00:28:22,800 --> 00:28:26,794
I see. Well, did you like
Hey, Hey, in the Hayloft?

457
00:28:26,972 --> 00:28:30,410
- Oh, I was crazy about that.
- I thought that would just about fit.

458
00:28:30,410 --> 00:28:32,979
- You remember the scene where
the two are in the hayloft?
- Perfectly.

459
00:28:32,980 --> 00:28:36,285
And she made him close his eyes
and count three before kissing her.

460
00:28:36,285 --> 00:28:38,420
- Yes, yes.
- And then the pig came out
and he kissed the pig instead.

461
00:28:38,421 --> 00:28:40,423
- It was on a very high plane.
- [ Laughing ]

462
00:28:40,423 --> 00:28:42,425
Then he fell through a hole
and sneezed at a horse.

463
00:28:42,426 --> 00:28:44,695
And the horse sneezed
back at him.

464
00:28:44,696 --> 00:28:46,765
Oh, that was
a wonderful scene.

465
00:28:46,765 --> 00:28:50,759
Of course it was stupid, but it was
wonderful. Who directed that picture?

466
00:28:52,306 --> 00:28:54,474
Don't you think with the world
in its present condition,

467
00:28:54,475 --> 00:28:56,711
with death snarling at you
from every street corner,

468
00:28:56,711 --> 00:28:59,314
that people are a little
allergic to comedies?

469
00:28:59,315 --> 00:29:02,251
- No.
- Perhaps I didn't make myself clear.

470
00:29:02,252 --> 00:29:05,355
Say, how come you know a picture
director well enough to borrow his car?

471
00:29:05,356 --> 00:29:08,326
As a matter of fact,
I used to know most of those boys,

472
00:29:08,327 --> 00:29:11,463
but naturally I don't
like to mention it in a suit like this.

473
00:29:11,464 --> 00:29:15,458
As a matter of fact,
I used to be a picture director.

474
00:29:15,536 --> 00:29:18,672
- Why, you poor kid.
- Don't get emotional.
I'll be all right.

475
00:29:18,673 --> 00:29:20,675
What kind of pictures
did you make?

476
00:29:20,676 --> 00:29:23,412
- More along educational lines.
- Oh, no wonder.

477
00:29:23,413 --> 00:29:26,416
There's nothing like a deep-dish movie
to drive you out in the open.

478
00:29:26,416 --> 00:29:28,418
What are you talking about?

479
00:29:28,419 --> 00:29:30,688
Film's the greatest educational
medium the world has ever known.

480
00:29:30,689 --> 00:29:33,859
- You take a picture like
Hold Back Tomorrow.
- You hold it.

481
00:29:33,860 --> 00:29:35,862
- Did you ever meet Lubitsch?
- Yes.

482
00:29:35,862 --> 00:29:37,864
Gee, I bet he wouldn't even
speak to you now.

483
00:29:37,865 --> 00:29:41,637
- He spoke to me day before yesterday.
- Isn't that swell.

484
00:29:41,637 --> 00:29:44,706
Funny, isn't it-- to meet
your first picture director...

485
00:29:44,707 --> 00:29:47,043
on the day you're leaving
Hollywood, all washed up--

486
00:29:47,044 --> 00:29:49,046
even a washed-up director.

487
00:29:49,046 --> 00:29:51,582
Don't get sympathetic.
I might make a comeback, you know.

488
00:29:51,583 --> 00:29:53,585
That's what they all say.
Man that had my room ahead of me--

489
00:29:53,586 --> 00:29:55,588
he was always going
to make a comeback.

490
00:29:55,588 --> 00:29:59,582
He was a picture director too.
Then one day he shot himself instead.

491
00:29:59,861 --> 00:30:02,330
They had to re-paper the room.

492
00:30:02,330 --> 00:30:05,333
You wouldn't ever do anything
like that would you, big boy?

493
00:30:05,334 --> 00:30:07,336
Not on your wallpaper.

494
00:30:07,337 --> 00:30:11,331
[ Siren Wailing ]

495
00:30:12,311 --> 00:30:14,313
What do you suppose that is?

496
00:30:14,313 --> 00:30:16,315
Whatever it is, there's
absolutely nothing they can do.

497
00:30:16,316 --> 00:30:18,051
Remember that.

498
00:30:18,051 --> 00:30:21,087
- What did you say?
- I said there's absolutely
nothing they can do.

499
00:30:21,088 --> 00:30:25,082
[ Metal Clanking ]

500
00:30:26,896 --> 00:30:30,890
- All right, you.
- All right yourself.
Don't give it a thought.

501
00:30:33,738 --> 00:30:35,740
Well?

502
00:30:35,741 --> 00:30:38,377
Oh, good morning, sir.

503
00:30:38,378 --> 00:30:40,513
- I'm so sorry.
- Good morning, sir.

504
00:30:40,513 --> 00:30:43,083
- Ever seen this man before?
- That is Mr. Sullivan, sir,

505
00:30:43,084 --> 00:30:46,722
- the owner of the alleged hot car.
- Then what's all the hullabaloo?

506
00:30:46,722 --> 00:30:47,923
That's what I'd like to know.

507
00:30:47,924 --> 00:30:49,926
- YouJohn L. Sullivan?
- What about it?

508
00:30:49,926 --> 00:30:51,928
- What's your occupation?
- Motion picture director.

509
00:30:51,929 --> 00:30:53,931
- That right?
- Yes, sir.

510
00:30:53,931 --> 00:30:55,933
Let me see
your driver's license.

511
00:30:55,934 --> 00:30:57,936
- I haven't got it. Did you bring it?
- No, sir.

512
00:30:57,937 --> 00:30:59,939
- Driving without a license, huh?
- Yes, isn't that terrible?

513
00:30:59,939 --> 00:31:02,675
I suppose that calls for a dollar fine
and ten minutes in jail.

514
00:31:02,676 --> 00:31:04,945
- You sure this is Sullivan?
- Oh, quite, sir.

515
00:31:04,946 --> 00:31:08,940
- What are you doing in those clothes?
- I just paid my income tax.

516
00:31:09,418 --> 00:31:11,820
- All right, but you don't drive
that car without a license.
- Okay.

517
00:31:11,821 --> 00:31:14,758
Let the girl out too.
She's getting bored in there.

518
00:31:14,759 --> 00:31:16,761
How does a girl fit
in this picture?

519
00:31:16,761 --> 00:31:18,763
There's always a girl
in the picture.

520
00:31:18,764 --> 00:31:20,766
Haven't you ever been
to the movies?

521
00:31:20,767 --> 00:31:23,936
Where's he taking us now?
Whose car is this?

522
00:31:23,937 --> 00:31:26,206
- The same guy. Sullivan.
- Where's he taking us?

523
00:31:26,206 --> 00:31:30,211
Down to the depot to buy you a ticket
and send you home. Stop fooling around.

524
00:31:30,212 --> 00:31:32,782
- Who's buying me a ticket?
- Sullivan.

525
00:31:32,782 --> 00:31:36,776
- What did I ever do for him?
- You bought him some eggs.

526
00:31:40,659 --> 00:31:43,529
Oh. So you're
the washed-up director.

527
00:31:43,530 --> 00:31:45,532
I'm afraid I exaggerated
that part of it a little bit.

528
00:31:45,532 --> 00:31:47,534
What are you doing
in those clothes?

529
00:31:47,535 --> 00:31:49,537
- I just pulled that one
down at the police station.
- Huh?

530
00:31:49,537 --> 00:31:52,139
I made up a joke.
Look, I'm not sore at you.

531
00:31:52,140 --> 00:31:54,976
I'm sore at those cops
for dragging me all the way back here.

532
00:31:54,977 --> 00:31:58,682
No matter where I start out for,
I always end up right back here
in Hollywood.

533
00:31:58,682 --> 00:32:01,819
You're a very nice girl, as a matter
of fact, and I'm glad to have met you.

534
00:32:01,820 --> 00:32:05,124
If there's ever anything I can do
for you, I'd be delighted. Honestly.

535
00:32:05,124 --> 00:32:07,126
- You mean that?
- Sincerely.

536
00:32:07,127 --> 00:32:11,121
Then buy me some ham and eggs
before I bite you.

537
00:32:12,568 --> 00:32:16,562
Home.

538
00:32:25,217 --> 00:32:27,219
Where's the swimming pool?

539
00:32:27,220 --> 00:32:29,655
You must have a swimming pool.

540
00:32:29,656 --> 00:32:33,650
Right out here.

541
00:32:35,231 --> 00:32:37,233
Outside dining room,

542
00:32:37,233 --> 00:32:41,227
- barbecue--
- Hmm.

543
00:32:44,609 --> 00:32:46,611
Pretty, isn't it?

544
00:32:46,612 --> 00:32:48,614
Yeah.

545
00:32:48,615 --> 00:32:50,683
There's the tennis court
up there,

546
00:32:50,683 --> 00:32:53,253
grape arbor there,
and a grove there.

547
00:32:53,254 --> 00:32:55,689
I guess that's about all.

548
00:32:55,690 --> 00:32:59,684
- What are you looking
at me that way for?
- [ Grunts ]

549
00:33:02,533 --> 00:33:04,902
- Hey, you big fathead!
- What's the big idea?

550
00:33:04,903 --> 00:33:06,971
That's for your swimming pools
and your tennis courts...

551
00:33:06,971 --> 00:33:08,673
and your limousines
and your barbecues.

552
00:33:08,674 --> 00:33:10,976
That's for making fun of a poor girl
who only tried to help you,

553
00:33:10,977 --> 00:33:13,179
-you big faker!
- Who made fun of you?

554
00:33:13,179 --> 00:33:16,249
You did, with your stories of being
a washed-up director, you big clunk.

555
00:33:16,250 --> 00:33:20,244
- Oh, I did, did I?
- [ Screaming ]

556
00:33:22,625 --> 00:33:25,896
[ Laughing ]

557
00:33:25,896 --> 00:33:29,890
Breakfast is served, sir.

558
00:33:30,368 --> 00:33:33,605
- You might have shaved.
- I need these whiskers
for my experiment.

559
00:33:33,606 --> 00:33:36,375
- Yes, the noble experiment.
- You don't have to make any cracks.

560
00:33:36,376 --> 00:33:38,712
I don't suffer and starve
because I like it, you know.

561
00:33:38,713 --> 00:33:40,715
Neither does anybody else.

562
00:33:40,716 --> 00:33:42,851
- I'm sorry.
- It's all right.

563
00:33:42,851 --> 00:33:45,721
- I'm sorry I pushed you
in the water too.
- I probably needed it.

564
00:33:45,722 --> 00:33:48,091
- You certainly did.
- Did I?

565
00:33:48,092 --> 00:33:52,097
I didn't mind you. As a matter of fact,
I had kind of a yen for you.

566
00:33:52,097 --> 00:33:54,099
- You have?
- Not in that thing.

567
00:33:54,100 --> 00:33:56,102
I liked you better as a tramp.

568
00:33:56,102 --> 00:33:58,404
[ Sullivan ] I can't help
what kind of people you like.

569
00:33:58,405 --> 00:34:01,408
It's funny. I suppose
I ought to be very happy for you,

570
00:34:01,409 --> 00:34:03,411
as if you'd just
struck oil or something.

571
00:34:03,412 --> 00:34:05,681
Instead of that, I'm sore.

572
00:34:05,681 --> 00:34:08,417
Don't frown.
You're making lines on your face.

573
00:34:08,418 --> 00:34:10,420
You've taken all
the joy out of life.

574
00:34:10,421 --> 00:34:12,423
I was all through
with this kind of stuff.

575
00:34:12,423 --> 00:34:15,961
I knew I'd never have it,
but there was no envy in my heart.

576
00:34:15,962 --> 00:34:18,398
I'd found a friend who swiped
a car to take me home.

577
00:34:18,398 --> 00:34:20,400
Now I'm right back
where I started--

578
00:34:20,401 --> 00:34:24,106
just an extra girl having
breakfast with a director,

579
00:34:24,106 --> 00:34:26,408
only I didn't used to have
breakfast with them.

580
00:34:26,409 --> 00:34:28,978
- Maybe that was my trouble.
- Did they ever ask you to?

581
00:34:28,979 --> 00:34:31,849
- No.
- Then don't pat yourself on the back.

582
00:34:31,849 --> 00:34:33,984
- Take me with you.
- What?

583
00:34:33,985 --> 00:34:36,921
On your experiment.
I don't want to be sent home.

584
00:34:36,922 --> 00:34:39,225
Don't be childish.
I'll tell you what I'll do.

585
00:34:39,226 --> 00:34:41,228
You can stay here for a couple of weeks
like I told you in the owl wagon,

586
00:34:41,228 --> 00:34:43,230
and when I get back,
I'll see what I can do for you.

587
00:34:43,231 --> 00:34:45,266
I don't want to start
all that stuff again.

588
00:34:45,267 --> 00:34:47,269
Take me with you.

589
00:34:47,269 --> 00:34:49,271
When you get as far as you're going,
we can say good-bye...

590
00:34:49,272 --> 00:34:51,274
and I'll go the rest
of the way alone.

591
00:34:51,274 --> 00:34:54,110
It'll make a nice ending, and we'll
finish what we started this morning.

592
00:34:54,111 --> 00:34:56,213
It's absolutely
out of the question.

593
00:34:56,214 --> 00:34:58,884
Please. You don't know
anything about anything.

594
00:34:58,885 --> 00:35:01,020
You don't know how to get a meal,
how to keep a secret,

595
00:35:01,020 --> 00:35:03,289
- and you can't even stay out of town.
- Thanks.

596
00:35:03,290 --> 00:35:06,160
I know 50 times as much
about trouble as you ever will.

597
00:35:06,161 --> 00:35:08,163
Besides, you owe it to me.

598
00:35:08,164 --> 00:35:11,768
You sort of belong to me.
When you were a hobo, I found you.

599
00:35:11,768 --> 00:35:13,770
- Piffle.
- Please.

600
00:35:13,770 --> 00:35:16,473
- It's absolutely out of the question.
- I'll throw you in the water.

601
00:35:16,474 --> 00:35:18,109
You'd take my mind off my work.

602
00:35:18,110 --> 00:35:21,080
[ Laughs ] The big director that has
all the girls panting for him.

603
00:35:21,081 --> 00:35:23,083
- I tell you--
- I'll follow you.

604
00:35:23,083 --> 00:35:25,085
I'll tell everybody who you are,
like a kid sister.

605
00:35:25,086 --> 00:35:26,721
You'll follow me?

606
00:35:26,721 --> 00:35:29,991
Yes, I'll follow you,
and I'll holler, ''This guy's a phony.

607
00:35:29,991 --> 00:35:32,127
''This is Sullivan,
the big director from Hollywood--

608
00:35:32,128 --> 00:35:34,130
a phonus-balonus, a faker, a heel--''

609
00:35:34,131 --> 00:35:36,133
If I may join in
the controversy, sir,

610
00:35:36,133 --> 00:35:38,135
I think the young lady's
suggestion an excellent one.

611
00:35:38,136 --> 00:35:40,138
- You may not join in the controversy.
- I will, I will, I will!

612
00:35:40,138 --> 00:35:42,140
- I'm going with you!
- You'll do nothing of the kind.

613
00:35:42,141 --> 00:35:44,744
Would you get me some
tramp clothes, Mr. Burrows?

614
00:35:44,745 --> 00:35:47,547
- Certainly, Miss. Certainly.
- Go down to the station
and get me a ticket to--

615
00:35:47,548 --> 00:35:50,418
- Where do you live?
- I won't tell you.
I won't be sent home.

616
00:35:50,419 --> 00:35:53,322
You stop that! Now, stop that!
Grab her feet!

617
00:35:53,322 --> 00:35:55,324
Oh! Yes, sir, yes, sir.
Certainly, sir.

618
00:35:55,325 --> 00:35:58,996
- Now, miss-- Now, miss--
Stop it, please, miss!
- I won't be sent home!

619
00:35:58,996 --> 00:36:02,990
- Let go of me!
- Oh, my!

620
00:36:08,142 --> 00:36:10,844
Mr. Burrows--
This way, Mr. Burrows.

621
00:36:10,845 --> 00:36:14,839
There we are.
Now, one, two, three-- Pull hard!

622
00:36:20,291 --> 00:36:23,294
Hello, Information?
Have you any freight trains...

623
00:36:23,295 --> 00:36:26,431
going east this afternoon
or early this evening?

624
00:36:26,432 --> 00:36:29,002
5:48?
Thank you very much, sir.

625
00:36:29,002 --> 00:36:32,005
Oh, and could you tell me,
does that train carry tramps,

626
00:36:32,006 --> 00:36:34,175
and if so,
where do they get on?

627
00:36:34,176 --> 00:36:38,014
What? It's on page two.

628
00:36:38,014 --> 00:36:40,550
- What did you say?
- Tramps.

629
00:36:40,551 --> 00:36:44,545
How would you like
to take a flying-- Wise guy.

630
00:36:44,589 --> 00:36:46,591
Yes, sir?

631
00:36:46,592 --> 00:36:49,228
What was that again?

632
00:36:49,229 --> 00:36:52,199
I said I wonder if you'd be
kind enough to settle a bet for us.

633
00:36:52,200 --> 00:36:54,202
Just a few of us
here at the club.

634
00:36:54,202 --> 00:36:56,604
If a tramp were to board
your 5:48 this afternoon,

635
00:36:56,605 --> 00:36:58,607
from where would he board it?

636
00:36:58,608 --> 00:37:02,613
I see. I see. Yes--
but not within the yard limits.

637
00:37:02,613 --> 00:37:04,615
I think that gives me
the complete picture.

638
00:37:04,615 --> 00:37:06,617
Thank you very much
for your trouble.

639
00:37:06,618 --> 00:37:08,620
Oh, and by the way, I win.

640
00:37:08,621 --> 00:37:10,623
[ Laughs ] Good day.

641
00:37:10,623 --> 00:37:14,617
A different approach
to the same problem.

642
00:37:20,870 --> 00:37:24,864
[ Train Whistle Blows ]

643
00:37:30,349 --> 00:37:34,343
I think this is it, sir.

644
00:37:37,525 --> 00:37:39,594
Why don't you go
back with the car.

645
00:37:39,594 --> 00:37:41,897
You look about as much
like a boy as Mae West.

646
00:37:41,898 --> 00:37:44,066
All right, they'll
think I'm your frail.

647
00:37:44,067 --> 00:37:46,570
I believe it's called
a ''beazel,'' miss, if memory serves.

648
00:37:46,570 --> 00:37:49,072
- Good-bye, Burrows.
See you in a couple of weeks.
- [ All ] Good-bye.

649
00:37:49,073 --> 00:37:52,076
May I close, sir, by warning you
against the entire expedition,

650
00:37:52,077 --> 00:37:54,213
which I envision
with deep apprehension...

651
00:37:54,214 --> 00:37:57,551
- and gloomy foreboding.
- Thanks. Same to you.

652
00:37:57,551 --> 00:38:00,923
Come on.

653
00:38:00,923 --> 00:38:04,627
[ Bells Ringing ]

654
00:38:04,627 --> 00:38:08,621
[ Train Whistle Blows,
Engine Chugging ]

655
00:38:22,450 --> 00:38:26,444
[ Whistle Blows ]

656
00:38:38,338 --> 00:38:42,332
[ Clamoring ]

657
00:39:12,082 --> 00:39:16,076
-Jump!
- [ Groans ]

658
00:39:23,096 --> 00:39:25,532
[ Woman ]
Come on. Here.

659
00:39:25,533 --> 00:39:29,527
I'll help you.

660
00:39:31,808 --> 00:39:35,802
- Let me up!
- I've got you!

661
00:39:45,659 --> 00:39:49,653
- We made it!
- Yeah.

662
00:39:50,165 --> 00:39:54,159
Amateurs.

663
00:40:00,813 --> 00:40:04,807
Phew!

664
00:40:05,318 --> 00:40:09,312
Oh. How do you do?

665
00:40:09,490 --> 00:40:13,484
- Beautiful weather.
- If it doesn't rain.

666
00:40:18,135 --> 00:40:22,129
How do you feel about
the labor situation?

667
00:40:23,843 --> 00:40:27,837
Where are you going?

668
00:40:32,153 --> 00:40:36,147
I hope we didn't disturb you.

669
00:40:39,295 --> 00:40:42,432
- Very interesting couple.
- Yeah.

670
00:40:42,433 --> 00:40:44,435
[ Sniffing ]

671
00:40:44,436 --> 00:40:46,438
- Do you smell anything?
- I certainly do.

672
00:40:46,439 --> 00:40:48,708
- What does it smell like to you?
- Hogs.

673
00:40:48,708 --> 00:40:51,744
- That's what I was afraid of.
- I'm getting hungry.

674
00:40:51,745 --> 00:40:54,882
How can you possibly
be hungry when you just ate?

675
00:40:54,883 --> 00:40:57,886
I'm not a scientist.
All I know is I'm hungry.

676
00:40:57,887 --> 00:40:59,889
[ Sneezes ]

677
00:40:59,890 --> 00:41:02,325
You'd better tell the porter
to close the window.

678
00:41:02,326 --> 00:41:06,320
I didn't ask you to come along
in the first place. Now that you're--

679
00:41:07,466 --> 00:41:09,468
[ Sniffly ]
Don't start baking wise cracks.

680
00:41:09,469 --> 00:41:12,672
- Dough, sir.
- Blasted draft in here, at that.

681
00:41:12,673 --> 00:41:14,675
- Where is this train going?
- I don't know.

682
00:41:14,675 --> 00:41:17,411
- How long does it take to get there?
- I didn't ask you to come along.

683
00:41:17,412 --> 00:41:19,714
I think that's a perfectly
reasonable question.

684
00:41:19,715 --> 00:41:21,984
Haven't you got enough imagination
to pretend we're broke,

685
00:41:21,985 --> 00:41:24,655
hungry, homeless,
drifting in despair?

686
00:41:24,655 --> 00:41:28,649
Let's just sit here and try
to feel like a couple of tramps.

687
00:41:57,765 --> 00:42:00,034
- Cold?
- I'll be all right.

688
00:42:00,034 --> 00:42:03,037
- It's the desert.
- [ Yawning ] I'll be all right.

689
00:42:03,038 --> 00:42:05,341
As soon as this blasted thing
comes to a town someplace,

690
00:42:05,342 --> 00:42:07,344
I'll send for a car
and have you taken home.

691
00:42:07,345 --> 00:42:09,347
This is a lot
of''hokey-palokey.''

692
00:42:09,347 --> 00:42:11,749
This is a terrible way
to travel, with a girl.

693
00:42:11,750 --> 00:42:13,752
It's better with a girl than without
one. You would have frozen to death.

694
00:42:13,753 --> 00:42:17,491
If I go back,
will you go back with me?

695
00:42:17,491 --> 00:42:19,493
- [ Sniffly ] Dodsense.
- Then I won't go back, either.

696
00:42:19,493 --> 00:42:23,487
- You're so simple,
you're apt to get into trouble.
- Why do you think I'm here?

697
00:42:24,300 --> 00:42:26,302
Gee, I like that about you.

698
00:42:26,302 --> 00:42:28,304
You're like those knights
of old,

699
00:42:28,305 --> 00:42:30,540
who used to ride around
looking for trouble.

700
00:42:30,541 --> 00:42:33,979
- Who was it who rode
on a pure white horse?
- Lady Godiba.

701
00:42:33,979 --> 00:42:37,973
She must have been a nut. I bet
her husband was sore. Are you jealous?

702
00:42:38,385 --> 00:42:41,756
Why don't you shut up
and try to get some sleep.

703
00:42:41,756 --> 00:42:44,759
- Will you go to sleep too?
- I'll try.

704
00:42:44,760 --> 00:42:48,031
Why don't you try counting the hogs
jumping over a hedge?

705
00:42:48,031 --> 00:42:52,025
Listen, short britches--
[ Sniffs ]

706
00:42:54,005 --> 00:42:57,999
[ Groans ]

707
00:43:00,580 --> 00:43:04,574
[ Whistle Blows ]

708
00:43:21,874 --> 00:43:24,010
- What's that?
- Nothing. Just me.

709
00:43:24,011 --> 00:43:26,613
- What?
- I sneezed.

710
00:43:26,614 --> 00:43:29,751
- You what?
- I-- [ Sneezes ]

711
00:43:29,752 --> 00:43:32,355
- I sneezed.
- Oh, you poor darling.

712
00:43:32,356 --> 00:43:34,858
- Have you got hay fever?
- I think it's hog fever.

713
00:43:34,858 --> 00:43:36,827
[ Coughing ]

714
00:43:36,828 --> 00:43:38,896
Oh, you poor lamb.

715
00:43:38,897 --> 00:43:42,168
[ Sniffly ] It'll be alright
as soon as the sun gets a little warmer.

716
00:43:42,168 --> 00:43:45,506
Are you huggry?
You got me doing it.

717
00:43:45,506 --> 00:43:48,175
- Have we got any eating money?
- Ten cents.

718
00:43:48,176 --> 00:43:50,779
Can we spend it for breakfast,
or are you saving it for something?

719
00:43:50,779 --> 00:43:53,048
Look, I've already told you,
I'll send for a car for you and--

720
00:43:53,049 --> 00:43:55,051
I can't help it
if I'm good-natured.

721
00:43:55,052 --> 00:43:57,788
I like to be with you,
and it puts me in a good humor.

722
00:43:57,789 --> 00:44:00,658
You take lots of girls and made them
sleep in a hog sty all night,

723
00:44:00,658 --> 00:44:02,660
and then didn't tell them
where their breakfast was coming from...

724
00:44:02,661 --> 00:44:04,930
the next morning,
they wouldn't take it lying down.

725
00:44:04,931 --> 00:44:07,067
We'll find some
breakfast somewhere.

726
00:44:07,067 --> 00:44:10,805
- In some swill pail, I suppose.
- What do the other bubs do?

727
00:44:10,806 --> 00:44:12,975
They steal chickigs... chickens.

728
00:44:12,975 --> 00:44:15,043
and they roast them
over campfires...

729
00:44:15,044 --> 00:44:18,047
with baked potatoes
and green corn on the cob...

730
00:44:18,048 --> 00:44:20,751
- with melted butter--
- Shut up!

731
00:44:20,752 --> 00:44:22,754
- Where do they get the butter?
- They steal it.

732
00:44:22,754 --> 00:44:25,490
Well, they don't.
It isn't as easy as all that.

733
00:44:25,491 --> 00:44:27,493
There's a lot of suffering
in this world...

734
00:44:27,494 --> 00:44:30,197
- that ordinary people
don't know anything about.
- [ Sniffling ]

735
00:44:30,197 --> 00:44:32,766
- Now what's the badder?
- I'm hungry.

736
00:44:32,767 --> 00:44:36,761
Well--
[ Sneezes ]

737
00:44:41,913 --> 00:44:45,907
[ Whistle Blows ]

738
00:44:46,820 --> 00:44:48,822
Hey, there's a town up ahead.

739
00:44:48,822 --> 00:44:51,658
Let's get off
and see what happens.

740
00:44:51,659 --> 00:44:55,230
- What town is it?
- I don't know.
I suppose it's Hollywood.

741
00:44:55,230 --> 00:44:57,666
Look, there's a lunch stand.

742
00:44:57,667 --> 00:45:01,661
Come on.

743
00:45:13,554 --> 00:45:17,548
Come on. I can't keep
running along here all day.

744
00:45:18,060 --> 00:45:21,631
Here I come. Just a minute.

745
00:45:21,631 --> 00:45:25,625
Well, come on.

746
00:45:36,784 --> 00:45:40,778
- Did I hurt you any?
- Well, you didn't do me any good.

747
00:45:44,094 --> 00:45:48,088
Come on.
[ Sneezes ]

748
00:46:05,556 --> 00:46:09,550
[ Horn Honks ]

749
00:46:18,940 --> 00:46:21,342
A cup of coffee
and sinker for one.

750
00:46:21,343 --> 00:46:23,812
I never eat till noon.
It gives me indigestion.

751
00:46:23,812 --> 00:46:26,348
-Just make that two coffees.
- That'll be ten cents.

752
00:46:26,349 --> 00:46:30,343
That's all right.

753
00:46:30,956 --> 00:46:34,950
It's right here someplace.

754
00:46:35,661 --> 00:46:38,764
- Holy Boses.
- What's the matter?

755
00:46:38,765 --> 00:46:42,759
I must have spent id
at that owl wagon.

756
00:46:55,253 --> 00:46:57,823
- I'll never get rich.
- Oh, gee.

757
00:46:57,824 --> 00:47:00,126
You're a little richer
than you were.

758
00:47:00,127 --> 00:47:02,129
Hundreds of miles from everything,
cut off from the world,

759
00:47:02,129 --> 00:47:04,131
a taste of human kindness.

760
00:47:04,132 --> 00:47:06,835
I'll never forget it as long as I live.
What town is this?

761
00:47:06,836 --> 00:47:10,707
- Las Vegas, Nevada.
- Las Vegas, Devada. This is the busy--

762
00:47:10,707 --> 00:47:14,701
- Las Vegas! You mean Las Vegas?
- What about it?

763
00:47:15,079 --> 00:47:17,081
Is there a land yacht
waiting here?

764
00:47:17,082 --> 00:47:21,076
Land yacht?
You mean that thing?

765
00:47:27,829 --> 00:47:29,831
That's perfectly wonderful,
Mr. Sullivan.

766
00:47:29,832 --> 00:47:31,834
I rejoice in your experience.

767
00:47:31,834 --> 00:47:34,103
- And where does this gentleman live?
-Just up there by the tracks.

768
00:47:34,104 --> 00:47:36,874
- Gib him $1 00. Never mind who from.
- That's swell.

769
00:47:36,875 --> 00:47:38,877
- A great human-interest story.
- It'll probably ruin him.

770
00:47:38,878 --> 00:47:41,213
He'll give turkey dinners
to every slug that comes in...

771
00:47:41,213 --> 00:47:43,215
and never
hit the jackpot again.

772
00:47:43,216 --> 00:47:45,218
All right, all right.
Buy the kid here a few clothes,

773
00:47:45,218 --> 00:47:47,320
and beet me in Kansas City,
someplace near the station.

774
00:47:47,321 --> 00:47:49,457
I'm going the hard way.
So long, gang.

775
00:47:49,458 --> 00:47:53,263
Just a minute, please.
Sit down!

776
00:47:53,263 --> 00:47:55,999
- But listen, Doc!
- You listen.

777
00:47:56,000 --> 00:47:59,136
It's three days in bed, minimum.

778
00:47:59,137 --> 00:48:03,131
- This is just a cold shot.
You won't even feel it.
- Yow!

779
00:48:03,176 --> 00:48:06,145
- I haven't time to spend
three days in bed.
- You'll take the time.

780
00:48:06,146 --> 00:48:08,148
You'll get to Kansas City
just as soon, and you can imagine...

781
00:48:08,149 --> 00:48:11,721
that you went there on your
cow snatcher, or whatever you used.

782
00:48:11,721 --> 00:48:15,715
What have you got
an imagination for?

783
00:48:17,094 --> 00:48:19,096
- Here's something for you.
- What's that?

784
00:48:19,097 --> 00:48:23,091
It's Christmas. So long.

785
00:48:34,417 --> 00:48:37,420
[ Knock At Door ]

786
00:48:37,421 --> 00:48:39,423
Come in!

787
00:48:39,423 --> 00:48:41,558
Here's a wrapper for you
and some slippers.

788
00:48:41,559 --> 00:48:43,895
- What?
- A wrapper.

789
00:48:43,896 --> 00:48:46,465
Oh, thanks.

790
00:48:46,465 --> 00:48:48,467
There's some makeup
in the medicine cabinet.

791
00:48:48,468 --> 00:48:52,462
- Thanks. I can use it.
- You sure can.

792
00:48:53,474 --> 00:48:57,446
Yes, sir, Mr. LeBrand, he's
in the next room taking a little snooze.

793
00:48:57,447 --> 00:49:00,785
He looks great. This whole thing
is doing him a power of good.

794
00:49:00,785 --> 00:49:04,779
[ Coughing ]

795
00:49:23,848 --> 00:49:25,850
[ Knock At Door]

796
00:49:25,850 --> 00:49:28,419
- Come in.
- Hello. Feel better?

797
00:49:28,420 --> 00:49:31,557
No, I'm sore. There's nothing
the matter with me but a little fever.

798
00:49:31,558 --> 00:49:34,561
Even if I did get sick, they could've
sent me to some free hospital.

799
00:49:34,562 --> 00:49:37,131
Wherever they send you.
It would have been very interesting.

800
00:49:37,132 --> 00:49:39,434
They give you a nice free burial too,
at Potter's Field.

801
00:49:39,435 --> 00:49:43,440
'' Free burial.'' Why does everybody
exaggerate everything so much?

802
00:49:43,440 --> 00:49:45,442
I've got a little cold in my head.

803
00:49:45,442 --> 00:49:47,444
You take a dose of salts,
and there you are.

804
00:49:47,445 --> 00:49:49,447
- It's because
you're a very valuable man.
- Bushwah.

805
00:49:49,448 --> 00:49:51,884
- You make very lovely pictures.
- Phooey.

806
00:49:51,884 --> 00:49:54,019
- Well, you do.
- It's a funny thing, how everything...

807
00:49:54,020 --> 00:49:57,458
keeps shoving me back to Hollywood
or Beverly Hills--

808
00:49:57,458 --> 00:49:59,460
[ Coughing ]

809
00:49:59,461 --> 00:50:03,455
Or this monstrosity we're riding in--
almost like gravity.

810
00:50:03,900 --> 00:50:07,036
As if some force were saying,
''Get back where you belong.

811
00:50:07,037 --> 00:50:10,308
You don't belong out here
in real life, you phony, you.''

812
00:50:10,308 --> 00:50:12,310
You're a little feverish.

813
00:50:12,311 --> 00:50:14,914
Baybe there's a universal law
that says, ''Stay put.

814
00:50:14,915 --> 00:50:17,184
As you are,
so shall you remain.''

815
00:50:17,184 --> 00:50:19,620
Maybe that's why tramps
are always in trouble.

816
00:50:19,621 --> 00:50:21,923
They don't vote.
They don't pay taxes.

817
00:50:21,924 --> 00:50:23,926
They violate the law of nature.

818
00:50:23,926 --> 00:50:25,928
You look very pretty
in that outfit.

819
00:50:25,929 --> 00:50:28,198
Maybe that's why they don't
want trailer colonies.

820
00:50:28,199 --> 00:50:31,937
- Or am I getting a bit profound?
- You're getting a bit hot.

821
00:50:31,937 --> 00:50:33,939
Your hand is very cool.

822
00:50:33,939 --> 00:50:35,941
But nothing is going stop me--

823
00:50:35,942 --> 00:50:38,945
I'm going to find out
how it feels to be in trouble,

824
00:50:38,946 --> 00:50:41,348
without friends, without credit,

825
00:50:41,349 --> 00:50:44,954
without checkbook,
without name-- alone.

826
00:50:44,954 --> 00:50:48,948
- And I'll go with you.
- How can I be alone if you're with me?

827
00:51:41,227 --> 00:51:45,221
~~ [ March ]

828
00:51:58,817 --> 00:52:02,811
[ No Audio ]

829
00:52:36,266 --> 00:52:40,260
[ No Audio ]

830
00:52:47,113 --> 00:52:51,107
[ No Audio ]

831
00:55:16,408 --> 00:55:20,402
[ No Audio ]

832
00:57:31,185 --> 00:57:33,654
Yes, sir, Mr. LeBrand.
It's all finished.

833
00:57:33,655 --> 00:57:35,924
the greatest expedition
of modern times,

834
00:57:35,924 --> 00:57:39,093
almost the greatest sacrifice
ever made by human man.

835
00:57:39,094 --> 00:57:41,597
- Good morning,Joseph.
- Yes, ma'am.

836
00:57:41,598 --> 00:57:44,234
- Good morning.
- Good morning.

837
00:57:44,235 --> 00:57:48,207
He's all washed up, except tonight
he's going through for a quick tour.

838
00:57:48,207 --> 00:57:50,542
He's taking $1 ,000
in $5.00 bills...

839
00:57:50,543 --> 00:57:54,537
and he's going to hand them out
to these tramps in gratitude
for what they done for him.

840
00:57:55,082 --> 00:57:58,085
Now is that a story? Does that
give you a lump in your throat,

841
00:57:58,086 --> 00:58:02,080
or does that give you
a lump in your throat?

842
00:58:08,833 --> 00:58:12,827
[ Snoring ]

843
00:58:20,249 --> 00:58:22,718
- Hello.
- Hello. Tired?

844
00:58:22,719 --> 00:58:26,590
No, no.
I was just thinking.

845
00:58:26,590 --> 00:58:30,128
Well, here we are
at the end of the adventure.

846
00:58:30,128 --> 00:58:34,066
I'll go down tonight and give them
a little money, and that winds it up.

847
00:58:34,066 --> 00:58:36,068
Now, what do you want to do?

848
00:58:36,069 --> 00:58:38,539
Do you want to go home
or take another crack at Hollywood?

849
00:58:38,539 --> 00:58:40,541
- Well, I--
- with a nice, fat letter to Lubitsch?

850
00:58:40,542 --> 00:58:44,079
I'd sort of like to...
go where you go.

851
00:58:44,079 --> 00:58:46,549
I mean, I'd sort of
hoped that you'd--

852
00:58:46,550 --> 00:58:49,820
Well, I mean, that you'd want us
to go on together a little longer,

853
00:58:49,820 --> 00:58:51,956
now that we kind of
got used to each other.

854
00:58:51,957 --> 00:58:55,261
-Of course I would, if I wasn't married.
-Who's married?

855
00:58:55,261 --> 00:58:58,264
Didn't you know that? I thought
everyone had heard of my misfortune.

856
00:58:58,265 --> 00:59:00,568
- Of course I didn't.
- What do you mean?

857
00:59:00,568 --> 00:59:03,103
As if I'd snatched you
away from your loving grandmother.

858
00:59:03,104 --> 00:59:05,106
- Are you in love with her?
- That vulture?

859
00:59:05,107 --> 00:59:07,109
- Then why did you marry her?
- Income tax.

860
00:59:07,109 --> 00:59:10,714
- Income tax?
- It was supposed to save me
$2 4,000 a year.

861
00:59:10,714 --> 00:59:13,283
It's what's called a joint return.
It's California law.

862
00:59:13,284 --> 00:59:16,287
Each one pays half, and the total
is less than the aggregate surtax,

863
00:59:16,288 --> 00:59:18,290
so the surtax is less
than the something or other.

864
00:59:18,291 --> 00:59:20,594
It was an idea
of my business manager's.

865
00:59:20,594 --> 00:59:23,129
- I think it's disgusting.
- It wasn't supposed to be romantic.

866
00:59:23,130 --> 00:59:26,602
It was supposed to save me
$1 2,000 a year, but it didn't.

867
00:59:26,602 --> 00:59:29,137
- Turned out she couldn't live
on $1 2,000 a year.
- Good.

868
00:59:29,138 --> 00:59:32,342
- Lovely. She had to have $2 4,000.
- Good.

869
00:59:32,343 --> 00:59:35,212
Don't keep saying ''good'' all the time,
or I'll poke you in the nose.

870
00:59:35,213 --> 00:59:37,215
- Good.
- Now, listen.

871
00:59:37,216 --> 00:59:39,218
So I demanded the divorce
she'd promised me.

872
00:59:39,218 --> 00:59:41,253
And she told you
to go fry an egg.

873
00:59:41,254 --> 00:59:43,256
She said it would break
her mother's heart.

874
00:59:43,256 --> 00:59:45,659
Some fine advice
your business manager gave you.

875
00:59:45,660 --> 00:59:48,931
I found out why.
He was getting half.

876
00:59:48,931 --> 00:59:51,934
- And you really can't
get a divorce ever?
- Never.

877
00:59:51,935 --> 00:59:54,638
You can't get a divorce without
collusion, and she won't collude.

878
00:59:54,639 --> 00:59:58,633
I guess
I ought to go home, then.

879
00:59:58,977 --> 01:00:02,147
You could still have
that letter to Lubitsch.

880
01:00:02,148 --> 01:00:05,986
Could I still come and push you
in the pool sometimes?

881
01:00:05,986 --> 01:00:09,858
- Of course you could.
- I guess that's better than nothing.

882
01:00:09,859 --> 01:00:12,128
There, there, there.
My gracious.

883
01:00:12,128 --> 01:00:14,864
Here are the $5.00 bills,
Mr. Sullivan.

884
01:00:14,865 --> 01:00:16,867
Hello,Johnnie.

885
01:00:16,868 --> 01:00:18,870
Get me two tickets
on the midnight plane.

886
01:00:18,870 --> 01:00:22,864
Two tickets? Oh, two tickets!
Yes, indeed, Mr. Sullivan.

887
01:00:23,176 --> 01:00:26,012
- They're pretty, aren't they?
- Uh-huh.

888
01:00:26,013 --> 01:00:28,182
- Do you want one?
- Yes.

889
01:00:28,182 --> 01:00:32,176
Here. You can have two of them.

890
01:01:55,029 --> 01:01:59,023
[ Train Whistle Blows ]

891
01:02:25,869 --> 01:02:29,863
[ Whistle Blows, Engine Chugging ]

892
01:03:59,658 --> 01:04:03,652
[ Train's Horn Honks ]

893
01:04:05,499 --> 01:04:09,504
[ Honking Continues ]

894
01:04:09,504 --> 01:04:13,498
[ Honking Continues ]

895
01:04:16,648 --> 01:04:20,642
[ Honking Continues ]

896
01:04:50,058 --> 01:04:52,060
[ Sighs ]

897
01:04:52,060 --> 01:04:54,562
Did you cancel the plane tickets?

898
01:04:54,563 --> 01:04:58,557
They cancel themselves. I'm gonna give
him just 1 5 minutes more, and then--

899
01:04:59,504 --> 01:05:01,506
I'm sure he's all right.

900
01:05:01,506 --> 01:05:04,208
He probably got interested
in a revival meeting or something and--

901
01:05:04,209 --> 01:05:06,712
[ Phone Rings ]

902
01:05:06,713 --> 01:05:10,707
Hello? Yes, Doc.

903
01:05:11,085 --> 01:05:14,088
Not in the hospitals, huh?

904
01:05:14,089 --> 01:05:16,658
Sure. I guess
that's all you can do.

905
01:05:16,659 --> 01:05:19,595
- Anyway, he didn't have an accident.
- [ Phone Rings ]

906
01:05:19,596 --> 01:05:21,799
Oh?

907
01:05:21,800 --> 01:05:24,669
He isn't, huh?

908
01:05:24,669 --> 01:05:27,372
Val has covered
the police stations.

909
01:05:27,373 --> 01:05:30,744
- Okay.
- I guess you can come back now.

910
01:05:30,744 --> 01:05:33,213
I should have gone with him.
I knew he'd get into trouble without me.

911
01:05:33,214 --> 01:05:35,483
- I told him that--
- I'll gonna give him
just 1 2 minutes more,

912
01:05:35,484 --> 01:05:38,220
Then I'm gonna lay it in LeBrand's lap
and let him figure it out.

913
01:05:38,221 --> 01:05:40,757
- Sully'll be awfully sore if you--
- Let him be sore.

914
01:05:40,757 --> 01:05:43,359
I got a job too, you know.
If LeBrand ever found out--

915
01:05:43,360 --> 01:05:46,898
- He came back the last time.
- He didn't have reservations
on a plane or people waiting.

916
01:05:46,898 --> 01:05:48,900
- You don't know him like I know him.
- Is that so?

917
01:05:48,901 --> 01:05:50,903
- I guess I know him better than--
- [ Rings ]

918
01:05:50,903 --> 01:05:53,906
- Yeah?
- Say, I'm down here to the morgue.

919
01:05:53,907 --> 01:05:56,777
They got a guy in a basket.
You can't tell who he is.

920
01:05:56,778 --> 01:05:59,380
Did the boss
have any identification?

921
01:05:59,381 --> 01:06:01,650
Did he have any identification
that you know of?

922
01:06:01,651 --> 01:06:04,654
Well, he had--
I think he said he had-- Who is that?

923
01:06:04,655 --> 01:06:06,791
- Have they found him?
- Take it easy.
We gotta check everywhere.

924
01:06:06,791 --> 01:06:10,662
- What identification did he have?
- In the soles of his shoes--

925
01:06:10,663 --> 01:06:13,934
I think there was a card
between the soles of his shoes.

926
01:06:13,934 --> 01:06:17,928
Look in the soles of his shoes,
between the leather.

927
01:06:25,415 --> 01:06:29,409
He's coming now.
I can hear his footsteps.

928
01:06:35,362 --> 01:06:39,356
There's a card here. It's kind of hard
to read. It's all splattered.

929
01:06:51,449 --> 01:06:54,887
- He's dead?
What do you mean, he's dead?
- What do you think it means?

930
01:06:54,887 --> 01:06:57,456
What do you send him on jobs like this
for? I've got a good mind to sue you.

931
01:06:57,457 --> 01:06:59,960
- Do you think I like it
any better than you do?
- I will sue you!

932
01:06:59,961 --> 01:07:03,499
I'll teach you to--
Operator? Operator,
I was talking with Kansas City.

933
01:07:03,499 --> 01:07:07,493
- She's gonna sue me.
- [ Scoffs ]

934
01:07:08,271 --> 01:07:11,408
I suppose I ought to fire
the whole bunch of you.

935
01:07:11,409 --> 01:07:14,680
Somehow I don't feel like
firing anybody.

936
01:07:14,680 --> 01:07:16,682
Well, there's no use
your hanging around here!

937
01:07:16,683 --> 01:07:18,685
Get your things together
and leave this afternoon!

938
01:07:18,686 --> 01:07:22,680
- I'll fly back.
- Yes, sir! Uh--

939
01:07:25,561 --> 01:07:29,555
[ Knock At Door ]

940
01:07:32,303 --> 01:07:36,297
[ Knocking Continues ]

941
01:07:48,725 --> 01:07:51,461
I'd like you to come
with us, my dear.

942
01:07:51,462 --> 01:07:53,864
Jones has explained to me.

943
01:07:53,864 --> 01:07:56,600
You were his last discovery--

944
01:07:56,601 --> 01:08:00,606
his last gift to the world.

945
01:08:00,606 --> 01:08:03,877
We'll take care of you always.

946
01:08:03,877 --> 01:08:07,871
She didn't hear you.

947
01:08:23,771 --> 01:08:27,765
[ Bells Clanging ]

948
01:09:46,945 --> 01:09:50,939
[ Groans ]

949
01:09:51,050 --> 01:09:53,186
- What's the idea,
riding into the yard?
- Huh?

950
01:09:53,187 --> 01:09:55,189
I said, what's the idea,
riding into the freight yard?

951
01:09:55,190 --> 01:09:58,628
- Lay off, will you?
- I've got a good mind to run
you in for trespassing.

952
01:09:58,628 --> 01:10:01,597
Shut up, you dumb cluck.
Can't you see I'm sick?

953
01:10:01,598 --> 01:10:04,201
Come on, get out of here,
you dirty rat!

954
01:10:04,201 --> 01:10:07,806
- Go on, go on!
- Don't do that again.

955
01:10:07,807 --> 01:10:10,943
- That's telling him, 'bo.
- Don't do what again?

956
01:10:10,944 --> 01:10:14,938
Come on. Come on, get going!

957
01:10:18,787 --> 01:10:22,781
[ Groans ]

958
01:10:28,233 --> 01:10:30,235
[ Man ]
Trespass. Resisting arrest.

959
01:10:30,235 --> 01:10:33,673
- Atrocious assault and battery
with intent to kill.
- Huh? What?

960
01:10:33,673 --> 01:10:35,775
- What did he say?
- We object, Your Honor.

961
01:10:35,776 --> 01:10:38,479
- My client had been injured
and denies all knowledge.
- Objection overruled.

962
01:10:38,480 --> 01:10:40,482
- Trespass and resisting arrest.
- Object,your honor.

963
01:10:40,483 --> 01:10:42,785
The man was a railroad employee,
not an officer of the law.

964
01:10:42,785 --> 01:10:45,654
- Sustained.
- Trespass and atrocious assault.

965
01:10:45,655 --> 01:10:47,657
- Objection, Your Honor.
- Objection overruled.

966
01:10:47,658 --> 01:10:49,794
Get down to business.
Prisoner at the bar.

967
01:10:49,794 --> 01:10:51,796
- [ Gavel Pounds ]
- Prisoner at the bar!

968
01:10:51,797 --> 01:10:54,066
- Answer when you're spoken to.
- Huh?

969
01:10:54,067 --> 01:10:57,638
- Do you plead guilty or not guilty?
- Huh?

970
01:10:57,638 --> 01:10:59,940
Guilty or not guilty to trespass
and atrocious assault...

971
01:10:59,941 --> 01:11:03,935
with a rock upon the person
of the employee of the railroad.

972
01:11:04,514 --> 01:11:08,508
I guess I hit him, all right,
the way my hand feels.

973
01:11:08,685 --> 01:11:11,822
I'm sorry.
I'll make it up to you.

974
01:11:11,823 --> 01:11:14,726
I'll pay any damages you like.
Sorry.

975
01:11:14,727 --> 01:11:16,795
So you still refuse
to give your name?

976
01:11:16,796 --> 01:11:19,099
It'll come back to me
in a minute.

977
01:11:19,099 --> 01:11:23,093
I have such an awful headache.
I'm all mixed up.

978
01:11:23,639 --> 01:11:25,841
We plead guilty, Your Honor,
with extenuating circumstances...

979
01:11:25,842 --> 01:11:29,078
due to temporary insanity, and throw
ourselves on the mercy of the court.

980
01:11:29,079 --> 01:11:31,649
Huh? What?
What did he say?

981
01:11:31,649 --> 01:11:34,685
Stand up. Stand up!

982
01:11:34,686 --> 01:11:38,680
Stand up.

983
01:11:41,895 --> 01:11:43,897
Prisoner at the bar,

984
01:11:43,898 --> 01:11:46,768
these are parlous times,
and we have no desire to be severe.

985
01:11:46,769 --> 01:11:48,871
-Just a minute. I--
- Silence!

986
01:11:48,872 --> 01:11:52,042
When confronted
with violence and hoodlumism,
the court has no alternative.

987
01:11:52,043 --> 01:11:54,211
Since you still refuse
to remember your name...

988
01:11:54,211 --> 01:11:56,380
but have pleaded guilty
to trespass and atrocious assault,

989
01:11:56,381 --> 01:11:59,217
I will be as lenient
as my conscience permits...

990
01:11:59,218 --> 01:12:03,212
and not impose upon you the maximum
penalty your crimes ordinarily permit.

991
01:12:03,991 --> 01:12:07,696
Richard Roe, I sentence you
to six years at hard labor...

992
01:12:07,696 --> 01:12:10,231
as prescribed by the laws
of our sovereign state.

993
01:12:10,232 --> 01:12:13,235
- [ Gavel Pounds ]
- Six years? What's he talking about?

994
01:12:13,236 --> 01:12:16,975
- You got off easy.
- Wait a minute.
I gotta get to a phone.

995
01:12:16,975 --> 01:12:18,977
- I have to send a--
- Come on.

996
01:12:18,978 --> 01:12:21,981
- Wait a minute. I'm all mixed up!
- Come on, come on!

997
01:12:21,982 --> 01:12:24,250
[ Horn Honking ]

998
01:12:24,251 --> 01:12:28,245
[ Barking ]

999
01:12:31,427 --> 01:12:35,421
Mister, new man.

1000
01:12:37,802 --> 01:12:39,804
- Hello, Charlie.
- Hi,Jake.

1001
01:12:39,804 --> 01:12:41,806
- Put him in 1 3.
-Just a minute, boys. I want to--

1002
01:12:41,807 --> 01:12:43,809
You speak when you're spoken to
around here. Hold up your arm and wait.

1003
01:12:43,810 --> 01:12:46,813
- Listen, you--
- You say '' Mister''
when you're talking to me.

1004
01:12:46,813 --> 01:12:49,249
- Put him in 1 3 and find him a bunk.
- Come on.

1005
01:12:49,250 --> 01:12:53,244
Wait a minute, wait a minute.
Them cost me $1 6.50.

1006
01:13:04,103 --> 01:13:08,097
- Another Richard Roe, eh?
- There seems to be a lot of them.

1007
01:13:08,275 --> 01:13:11,412
- How's everything
at the house, Charlie?
- Fine,Jake.

1008
01:13:11,413 --> 01:13:15,407
- Give my regards to the missus.
- I'll do that little thing.

1009
01:13:16,987 --> 01:13:19,122
- I gotta get out of here.
- Take it easy, boy.

1010
01:13:19,122 --> 01:13:21,124
I'm John L. Sullivan,
a Hollywood director.

1011
01:13:21,125 --> 01:13:23,861
- Somebody slugged me.
I gotta get out of here.
- A Hollywood what?

1012
01:13:23,862 --> 01:13:27,434
- [ Laughing ]
- Take it easy, will you?
You're gonna lose your privilege.

1013
01:13:27,434 --> 01:13:31,372
No letters, no smokes, no writing.
You don't want that.

1014
01:13:31,372 --> 01:13:33,374
I want a lawyer.
You get me to a telephone.

1015
01:13:33,375 --> 01:13:35,377
There's a telephone
right down there.

1016
01:13:35,377 --> 01:13:37,512
They can't do things like this
to people. Put 'em in a pigsty.

1017
01:13:37,513 --> 01:13:40,516
Pipe down, will you,
please, before he hears.

1018
01:13:40,517 --> 01:13:43,387
I want a lawyer. I demand
my right to have a lawyer!

1019
01:13:43,388 --> 01:13:45,423
Did you hear that?
He demands a lawyer.

1020
01:13:45,423 --> 01:13:49,417
[ Men Laughing ]

1021
01:13:50,130 --> 01:13:52,132
You starting in again?

1022
01:13:52,133 --> 01:13:55,369
You're gonna be here
a long time, see?

1023
01:13:55,370 --> 01:13:59,142
And you gotta learn,
and learn quick.

1024
01:13:59,142 --> 01:14:03,136
[ Thud ]

1025
01:14:06,852 --> 01:14:10,823
Chain him in.

1026
01:14:10,823 --> 01:14:14,817
No privilege, fresh guy.

1027
01:15:05,495 --> 01:15:09,489
We're going to
the picture show Sunday.

1028
01:15:10,468 --> 01:15:14,462
Good news. You want to see
the picture show Sunday?

1029
01:15:15,875 --> 01:15:19,869
We're going to the picture show.

1030
01:15:22,584 --> 01:15:25,053
We're going to the picture show Sunday.
They asked us over again.

1031
01:15:25,054 --> 01:15:27,022
- When can I write a letter?
- When you get your privilege back.

1032
01:15:27,023 --> 01:15:29,025
How long will that take?

1033
01:15:29,025 --> 01:15:30,994
That all depends on the Mister.

1034
01:15:30,995 --> 01:15:32,997
He's all right
if you take it nice and quiet.

1035
01:15:32,998 --> 01:15:35,133
How long does it take him
to make up his mind?

1036
01:15:35,133 --> 01:15:39,127
Take it easy, will you,
or you'll never get it.

1037
01:15:49,920 --> 01:15:53,914
Look out!

1038
01:15:54,893 --> 01:15:58,430
Who gave you leave to read the paper?
You won't learn, huh?

1039
01:15:58,430 --> 01:16:00,566
- It's about me.
I just happened to see it.
- Shut up!

1040
01:16:00,567 --> 01:16:03,503
Turn around. Turn around!

1041
01:16:03,504 --> 01:16:07,498
Put your hands behind you.

1042
01:16:08,578 --> 01:16:10,613
- Put him in the sweat box.
- For how long, Mister?

1043
01:16:10,613 --> 01:16:14,051
- Till I tell you.
Are you gonna start now?
- No. Yes. I mean no, sir.

1044
01:16:14,051 --> 01:16:18,045
Then get moving!

1045
01:16:19,158 --> 01:16:23,152
Get back to your work. What do you
think this is, a vaudeville show?

1046
01:16:38,583 --> 01:16:41,019
Tastes good, don't it?

1047
01:16:41,020 --> 01:16:45,014
I'll try to get him
to let you off early.

1048
01:16:47,428 --> 01:16:51,422
I ain't supposed to do this.

1049
01:17:22,340 --> 01:17:24,576
- Water.
- You'll be all right.

1050
01:17:24,577 --> 01:17:26,645
You got to learn, that's all.
It ain't so easy at first,

1051
01:17:26,646 --> 01:17:29,216
but after a while
you don't mind.

1052
01:17:29,216 --> 01:17:32,787
We ain't so bad off.
He ain't bad, according to his lights.

1053
01:17:32,787 --> 01:17:35,089
He has to deal with some
pretty tough hombres.

1054
01:17:35,090 --> 01:17:37,126
He got us chicken
last Thanksgiving...

1055
01:17:37,127 --> 01:17:40,130
and some turkey once
for Christmas.

1056
01:17:40,131 --> 01:17:43,100
And there ain't another Mister
takes his gang to the picture show.

1057
01:17:43,101 --> 01:17:47,095
Maybe-- Maybe if I ask him, he'll
let you go the picture show Sunday.

1058
01:17:47,807 --> 01:17:51,801
Wouldn't that
be something? Huh?

1059
01:17:52,379 --> 01:17:56,373
~~~[ Organ Playing ]

1060
01:18:00,123 --> 01:18:04,117
All right, Charlie.

1061
01:18:05,396 --> 01:18:07,398
Let it down easy, Charlie.

1062
01:18:07,399 --> 01:18:10,436
- [ People Laughing ]
- Charlie's a little anxious.

1063
01:18:10,437 --> 01:18:13,406
[ Laughter ]

1064
01:18:13,407 --> 01:18:17,401
Brothers and sisters, once again
we're gonna have a little entertainment.

1065
01:18:17,546 --> 01:18:19,681
I don't have to tell you
what it is.

1066
01:18:19,682 --> 01:18:23,420
The sheet kind of gives it away.

1067
01:18:23,420 --> 01:18:27,092
And once again, brothers and sisters,
we're going to share our pleasure...

1068
01:18:27,092 --> 01:18:31,097
with some neighbors
less fortunate than ourselves.

1069
01:18:31,097 --> 01:18:35,091
Won't you please clear the first
three pews so they may have seats.

1070
01:18:36,671 --> 01:18:40,375
And when they get here,
I'm gonna ask you once more,

1071
01:18:40,375 --> 01:18:44,369
neither by word, nor by action,
nor by look...

1072
01:18:44,682 --> 01:18:47,551
to make our guests feel
unwelcome.

1073
01:18:47,551 --> 01:18:51,545
Don't draw away from them
or act high-toned.

1074
01:18:52,125 --> 01:18:56,119
- For we is all equal
in the sight of God.
- Amen!

1075
01:18:57,264 --> 01:19:01,258
And He said,
'' Let him who is without sin...

1076
01:19:02,138 --> 01:19:04,707
- ''cast the first stone.
- [ All Shout Agreement ]

1077
